dson]], medievalist\n* [[A. C. Grayling]], philosopher\n* [[Vittorio Grilli]], Italy's economy and finances minister (Monti cabinet) from 2012 to 2013.\n* [[Richard Hamblyn]], lecturer in creative writing\n* [[Vanessa Harding (historian)|Vanessa Harding]], professor of London history\n* [[Basil Hiley]], quantum physicist and emeritus professor\n* [[Paul Hirst]], professor\n* [[Eric Hobsbawm]], Emeritus Professor of History\n* [[Thomas Hodgskin]], lecturer in economic theory\n* [[Kenneth Holmes]], crystallographer\n* [[C. E. M. Joad]], Reader in Philosophy, author and popular broadcaster\n* [[Mark H. Johnson (professor)|Mark Johnson]], professor\n* [[Charlotte Jolles]], Professor, historian\n* [[Russell Celyn Jones]], professor\n* [[Annette Karmiloff-Smith]], professor\n* [[Anthony Julius]], visiting professor\n* [[Aaron Klug]], crystallographer and Nobel Laureate for Chemistry, 1982\n* [[Jon Lansman]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] activist\n* [[Toby Litt]], author, lecturer\n* [[Joni Lovenduski]], political scientist\n* [[Mark Mazower]], professor\n* [[Louis Mordell]], researcher in mathematics\n* [[Laura Mulvey]], professor of film and media studies\n* [[Jeremy K. Nicholson]], professor of biological chemistry\n* [[Roger Penrose]], theoretical physicist\n* [[Nikolaus Pevsner]], professor\n* [[Ben Pimlott]], professor\n* [[Lucy Riall]], historian\n* [[Helen Saibil]], molecular biologist, FRS, FMedSci\n* [[Roger Scruton]], professor\n* [[Lynne Segal]], professor\n* [[Colin Teevan]], professor of playwriting\n* Dame [[Janet Thornton]], structural bioinformatics, [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]], Director [[European Bioinformatics Institute|EBI]]\n* [[Li Wei (linguist)|Li Wei]], academic, linguist\n* [[Ralph Vaughan Williams]], lecturer, composer\n* [[Tony Wright (Cannock Chase MP)|Tony Wright]], politician, distinguished professor at Birkbeck\n* [[Slavoj \u017di\u017eek]], philosopher\n\n==Presidents==\n* [[Eric Hobsbawm]], President of the college, Marxist historian of the rise of industrial capitalism, socialism, and nationalism\n* [[Joan Bakewell]], broadcaster, critic, President of Birkbeck College\n* [[George Birkbeck]] (1776\u20131841), doctor, philanthropist and founder of Birkbeck\n\n==Masters==\n* [[David Latchman]] 2003-present\n* [[Timothy O'Shea]] 1998\u20132002; Principal of the [[University of Edinburgh]]\n* [[Tessa Blackstone, Baroness Blackstone]] 1987\u20131997; Vice-Chancellor of [[University of Greenwich]]\n* [[Ronald Tress]] 1968\u20131977\n* [[Kenneth Hare]] 1966\u20131968\n* [[E. H. Warmington]] (acting) 1965\u20131966\n* [[John Francis Lockwood]] 1951\u20131965; Vice-Chancellor of the University of London 1955\u20131958\n* E. H. Warmington (acting) 1950\u20131951\n* [[John Redcliffe Maud]] 1939\u20131943\n\n==Alumni==\n* [[Mukhlesur Rahman Chowdhury]], politician, editor, Minister and former Adviser to the President of Bangladesh\n* [[Chris Abani]], writer\n* [[Marian Bell (economist)|Marian Bell]], economist; former member of the Monetary Policy Committee\n* [[Luciana Berger]], politician and Member of Parliament\n* [[Annie Besant]], theosophist\n* [[Simon Bird]], actor and comedian\n* [[Oliver Chris]], actor\n* [[Alex Corbisiero]], England and British Lions rugby player\n* [[Beth Cordingly]], actress\n* [[David Cox (statistician)|David Cox]], statistician\n* [[Bernard Crick]], political theorist\n* [[Juliet Davenport]], businesswoman\n* [[Alan Davey (civil servant)|Alan Davey]], civil servant; current Chief executive of [[Arts Council of Great Britain|British Arts Council]]\n* [[Edward Davey]], politician and Member of Parliament\n* [[Dido (singer)|Dido]], singer\n* [[Jennifer Donnelly]], writer\n* [[Samir El-Youssef]], writer\n* [[Tracey Emin]], artist\n* [[Nissim Ezekiel]], professor, poet\n* [[Rachel Glennerster]], economist, Chief Economist at the Department for International Development \n*[[Tom\u00e1s Gonz\u00e1lez Estrada]], Colombian politician, former minister of energy\n* [[Marcus Garvey]], founder [[Universal Negro Improvement Association and African Communities League]]\n* [[Eliane Glaser]], writer, broadcaster\n* [[Julia Goldsworthy]], politician; former [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] MP for [[Falmouth and Camborne (UK Parliament constituency)|Falmouth and Camborne]]\n* [[Bear Grylls]], adventurer, author and television presenter\n* [[John Joseph Haldane]], philosopher\n* [[Frank Hartley (pharmacist)|Frank Hartley]], vice-chancellor of the university\n* [[Zhu Hua]], applied linguist\n* [[Vernon Ingram]], Fellow of the Royal Society\n* [[Paul Johnson (economist)|Paul Johnson]], economist, Director of [[Institute of Fiscal Studies]]\n* [[William Joyce]], deputy Leader of the [[British Union of Fascists]], Nazi wartime broadcaster and convicted traitor<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uniset.ca/nold/1946AC347.pdf|title=Joyce Appellant; and Director of Public Prosecutions |year=1946 |publisher=House of Lords |page=1 |accessdate=20 September 2009}}</ref>\n* [[James Lovelock]], developer of the [[Gaia Hypothesis]]\n* [[Ramsay MacDonald]], politician; first Labour Prime Minister of the United Kingdom\n* [[John McDonnell (politician)|John McDonnell]], politician\n* [[Denis MacShane]], politician\n* [[Leonard Mandel]], nuclear physicist\n* [[Ehsan Masood]], science writer and editor of [[Research Fortnight]]\n* [[Ram Charan Mehrotra]], organometallic chemist, [[Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar Prize|Shanti Swarup Bhatnagar]] laureate\n* [[Ernest Millington]], politician\n* [[Seumas Milne]], journalist and political aide\n* [[Lisa Nandy]], politician and Member of Parliament\n* [[Jesse Norman]], politician and Member of Parliament\n* [[Nerina Pallot]], singer\n* [[Nick Palmer]], politician and former Member of Parliament\n* [[Arthur Wing Pinero]], actor, stage director and dramatist\n* [[Daisy Ridley]], actress\n* [[J. Philippe Rushton]], psychologist\n* [[John Rowan (psychologist)]], psychologist\n* [[Jenny Rowe]], Chief Executive, UK Supreme Court\n* [[Richard Sambrook]], broadcaster, formerly director of the BBC World\n* [[Frank Sando]], former International Cross-Country Champion\n* [[Andy Saull]], rugby player\n* [[Helen Sharman]], chemist and cosmonaut\n* [[Joost Smiers]], academic\n* [[Nick Smith (British politician)|Nick Smith]], politician\n* [[Vaughan Smith]], soldier, journalist, cameraman, and social entrepreneur\n* [[Laura Solomon]], writer\n* [[Nicola Spence]], Chief Plant Health Officer, [[Defra]]\n* [[William Stanley (inventor)|William Stanley]], inventor, engineer and philanthropist\n* [[Kim Thomson]], stage, film and television actress\n* [[Mark P. Taylor]], economist, Dean of Olin Business School at Washington University in St. Louis\n*[[Laurie Taylor (sociologist)|Laurie Taylor]], sociologist\n* [[Tracey Thorn]], pop star, singer with [[Everything but the Girl]]\n* [[Ronald Tress]], economist\n* [[Kitty Ussher]], British economist and former Labour Party politician\n*[[Alfred Russel Wallace]], naturalist, explorer, geographer, anthropologist, and biologist. He is best known for independently conceiving the theory of evolution through natural selection\n* [[Rob Williams (rower, born 1985)|Rob Williams]], rower, silver medallist in the 2012 Olympics\n* [[Sidney James Webb, 1st Baron Passfield]], founder of the [[London School of Economics]]\n* [[Jah Wobble]], musician/writer\n* [[Wai Hnin Pwint Thon]], [[Burmese Muslim]] [[political activist]]\n* [[Sidin Vadukut]], columnist, writer and blogger\n\n==Fellows==\n* [[Edward Davey]], Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Kingston and Surbiton (UK Parliament constituency)|Member of Parliament for Kingston and Surbiton]]\n* [[Frank Dobson]], Labour politician\n* Dame [[Vivien Duffield]], philanthropist\n* Sir [[Richard J. Evans]], historian\n* [[Julia Goodfellow]], former Chief Executive of the [[Biotechnology and Biological Sciences Research Council]]\n* Sir [[Peter Lampl]], educationalist and philanthropist, founder of the [[Sutton Trust]]\n* [[Leonard Wolfson, Baron Wolfson]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Birkbeck, University of London}}\n\n[[Category:Birkbeck, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Birkbeck, University of London| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by university or college in London|Birkbeck]]\n", "name_user": "Medievalfran", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCurrent and former faculty:added Gail Lewis.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Birkbeck,_University_of_London_people"}
{"title_page": "Love Ni Bhavai", "text_new": "{{one source|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name = Love Ni Bhavai\n|film_name   = \n|image = Love Ni Bhavai poster.jpg\n|caption = Theatrical release poster\n|director = [[Sandeep Patel]]\n|producer = Aarti Patel\n|writer  = Mitai Shukla<br />Nehal Bakshi\n|starring = [[Malhar Thakar]]<br />[[Pratik Gandhi]]<br />[[Aarohi Patel]]\n|music = [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n|cinematography = Tapan Vyas\n|editing = Prateek Gupta\n|released = {{Film date|2017|11|17}}\n|runtime= 146 minutes\n|country = [[India]]\n|language = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n|budget =\n|gross = {{INRConvert|8|c}} (India) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/movies/box-office/love-ni-bhavai-box-office-collections/EG00044121|title=Love Ni Bhavai Collections - Love Ni Bhavai Movie Box Office Collection - BookMyShow|website=in.bookmyshow.com|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Love Ni Bhavai''''' is a 2017 Gujarati [[romance film|romantic]] [[drama film]] directed by Sandeep Patel<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/web-series/news/manasi-parekh-gohil-turns-producer-dons-a-dual-role-of-actor-and-producer-for-do-not-disturb/articleshow/70672001.cms|title=Manasi Parekh Gohil turns producer; dons a dual role of actor and producer for 'Do Not Disturb' - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> and produced by Aarti Patel. Its plot is heavily based on the 2008 Hollywood Film [[The Accidental Husband]]. The background score and soundtrack was composed by [[Sachin-Jigar]], with lyrics from Niren Bhatt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://creativeyatra.com/reviews/love-ni-bhavai-speaks-language-contemporary-youth/|title=\u2018Love ni Bhavai\u2019 speaks the language of the contemporary youth|date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n{{rewrite section|date=March 2018}}\nRJ Antara, who works in a FM Radio, is loved by the entire Ahmedabad due to her energetic voice and solid attitude. She was against love and relationships initially and told her boss K (Krishna) that she would never fall in love that are meaningless and selfish. She was awarded the youngest RJ achiever award due to her contribution to the Radio.\nAditya, a rich business man, was once stuck in a heavy traffic. He observed Antara helping clearing the traffic and fell in love with her.\nIn the award ceremony, Antara met Aaditya. He tries to maintain relation with her. He considered her as his best friend and told her that he wants to see her happy, whether as a friend or anything else. Their regular talks became a headline news, and her boss K (Krishna) regularly teases her. Once Antara got a call from Swati, who asked her what to answer because her boyfriend Sagar was going to propose her on Valentines Day. (Sagar is the main actor of the film who got rejected by 23 girls, yet he was optimistic about someone agreeing on him). Antara asked Swati to listen to her heart and breakup with Sagar if she is not happy and doesn't see any future with him.\nConvinced, as a result, Swati rejects Sagar's proposal and breaks up with him. This disheartens Sagar to a great extent. He was somehow consoled by his father.\nLater, when Sagar learns that it was because of Antara's advise that Swati rejected him, he decides to take revenge on her by following her to the Diu Trip, falsely taking photos with her and making it a fake news in the newspaper in order to make Antara fall in trouble with headlines.\nHe along with his friend (who was a photographer) manages to get information about Antara's Diu trip and boards the same bus which she boarded. Sagar continues his talks with Antara and manages to befriend her.\nHowever, Sagar fell in love with her as he started spending time with her in the trip. He asked his friend to avoid posting the fake news until he tells him to do so.\nAntara also secretly felt for Sagar and she knew Sagar also felt for her.\nHowever, once when she was invited by Sagar for a birthday party at his home, she went to Sagar's room and checked all the pictures of her trip with Sagar in his laptop. This made her angry and hurt her a lot. She understood that Sagar didn't love her, but just used her to become famous.\nWhen she left the party, Sagar stopped her. She told everything. Sagar revealed about his anger on Antara when he came to know that her advise forced Swati to reject him. Antara realised that Sagar had planned a revenge and this hurt her more. She told Sagar not to talk with her henceforth.\nAaditya came to know about Sagar and Antara's Diu Trip, called Sagar to his office and warned him to stay away from Antara and avoid hurting her.\nLater, Aaditya proposed her for marriage, however Antara chose not to answer that.\nSagar then called her on her Radio Love Line and reminder her that without her, his life has become monotonous and he misses her alot.\nAntara ignored Sagar's calls and messages, and agreed to marry Aditya.\nSagar came to know about this and reached Antara's office, but her boss Krishna told Sagar to stay away from Antara and avoid hurting her more.\nBecause Antara was not responding Sagar's calls and messages, he sent her a letter asking whom she remembers the most when she gets up in the morning, when drinking coffee and when listening to songs online.\nSagar's friend later informs him that his boss is planning to post all the trip pictures in the newspaper next day to defame Antara.\nThis makes Sagar tense, but he somehow manages to delete all the pictures from the boss' laptop with the help of his friend and snatches the pen-drive having the backup, and throws it into the lake.\nAaditya happens to read the letter sent by Sagar at Antara's home when he came there to take out for coffee and he realised that she is not happy with the marriage.\nDespite asking Antara a lot, she chooses to stay quiet and marry Aditya.\nDuring the marriage, Aaditya meets Antara and asks her to say the truth of whom she really thinks of in her mind. When Antara could not answer, Aditya told her that his aim was to see her happy, whether with him or with anyone else. Aaditya understood her mind and agreed to help her meet Sagar (who had already started giving up on his relationship with Antara).\nHowever, they were not able to locate him. Antara reached Radio office and asked Ahmedabad City to help her find Sagar. She manages to get help from a Tea Vendor where Sagar was sitting.\nAntara reaches that place and proposes Sagar by saying that she wants to forget her earlier anger and wants to start a new relationship with him, to which Sagar happily accepts.\nSagar thanked Aditya for such a huge sacrifice of his life.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Pratik Gandhi]] as Aaditya Shah\n* [[Aarohi Patel]] as RJ Antara\n* [[Malhar Thakar]] as Sagar Desai\n* [[Ghanashyam Nayak|Maulik Nayak]]\n*Diana Raval\n*Roopa Divatia\n*Nisarg Trivedi\n\n==Soundtrack==\nSoundtrack album was composed by famous [[Bollywood]] composer duo [[Sachin-Jigar]]. 'Vhalam Aavo Ne' was presented as a lead soundtrack for the album. There are mainly four soundtrack presented with other three being variations of the main tracks. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer(s) !!  Length !!Lyrics !!Notes\n|-\n| 1 || Vhalam Aavo Ne || [[Jigardan Gadhavi]] || 05:19 || Niren Bhatt || Original version\n|-\n| 2 || Vhalam Aavo Ne \u2013 Sad(Female) || [[Aishwarya Majmudar]] || 02:24 || Niren Bhatt || Female sad version\n|-\n| 3 || Vhalam Aavo Ne \u2013 Sad(Male) || Jigardan Gadhavi || 01:44 || Niren Bhatt || Male sad version\n|-\n| 4 || Dhun Laagi || Siddharth Amit Bhavsar || 04:34 || Niren Bhatt || Original version\n|-\n| 5 || Dhun Laagi \u2013 Sad || Siddharth Amit Bhavsar || 01:47 || Niren Bhatt || Male sad version\n|-\n| 6 ||  Athdaya Karu Chhu || Punit Gandhi, Smita Nair Jain || 03:58 || Niren Bhatt || Only duet from album\n|-\n| 7 || I Love You Re Mari Savaar || [[Jonita Gandhi]] || 03:09 || Niren Bhatt || -\n|-\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nThe film achieved a critical and commercial success and ran for more than 100 days in the theatres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chitralekha.com/news/entertainment/love-ni-bhavai/|title=\u0ab5\u0acd\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab2\u0aae \u0a86\u0ab5\u0acb\u0aa8\u0ac7\u2026 \u0aae\u0abe\u0aa3\u0acb\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a86 \u0ab8\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab8\u0ac7\u0ab8-\u0a95\u0aa5\u0abe|date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title}}\n*Love Ni Bhavai [https://www.netflix.com/in/title/80990811] on [[Netflix]]\n*\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Gujarati-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Daman and Diu]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n\n\n{{India-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{one source|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n|name = Love Ni Bhavai\n|film_name   = \n|image = Love Ni Bhavai poster.jpg\n|caption = Theatrical release poster\n|director = [[Sandeep Patel]]\n|producer = Aarti Patel\n|writer  = Mitai Shukla<br />Nehal Bakshi\n|starring = [[Malhar Thakar]]<br />[[Pratik Gandhi]]<br />[[Aarohi Patel]]\n|music = [[Sachin-Jigar]]\n|cinematography = Tapan Vyas\n|editing = Prateek Gupta\n|released = {{Film date|2017|11|17}}\n|runtime= 146 minutes\n|country = [[India]]\n|language = [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]]\n|budget =\n|gross = {{INRConvert|8|c}} (India) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.bookmyshow.com/movies/box-office/love-ni-bhavai-box-office-collections/EG00044121|title=Love Ni Bhavai Collections - Love Ni Bhavai Movie Box Office Collection - BookMyShow|website=in.bookmyshow.com|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Love Ni Bhavai''''' is a 2017 Gujarati [[romance film|romantic]] [[drama film]] directed by Sandeep Patel<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/web-series/news/manasi-parekh-gohil-turns-producer-dons-a-dual-role-of-actor-and-producer-for-do-not-disturb/articleshow/70672001.cms|title=Manasi Parekh Gohil turns producer; dons a dual role of actor and producer for 'Do Not Disturb' - Times of India|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> and produced by Aarti Patel. Its plot is heavily based on the 2008 Hollywood Film [[The Accidental Husband]]. The background score and soundtrack was composed by [[Sachin-Jigar]], with lyrics from Niren Bhatt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://creativeyatra.com/reviews/love-ni-bhavai-speaks-language-contemporary-youth/|title=\u2018Love ni Bhavai\u2019 speaks the language of the contemporary youth|date=18 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n{{rewrite section|date=March 2018}}\nRJ Antara, who works in a FM Radio, is loved by the entire Ahmedabad due to her energetic voice and solid attitude. She was against love and relationships initially and told her boss K (Krishna) that she would never fall in love that are meaningless and selfish. She was awarded the youngest RJ achiever award due to her contribution to the Radio.\nAditya, a rich business man, was once stuck in a heavy traffic. He observed Antara helping clearing the traffic and fell in love with her.\nIn the award ceremony, Antara met Aaditya. He tries to maintain relation with her. He considered her as his best friend and told her that he wants to see her happy, whether as a friend or anything else. Their regular talks became a headline news, and her boss K (Krishna) regularly teases her. Once Antara got a call from Swati, who asked her what to answer because her boyfriend Sagar was going to propose her on Valentines Day. (Sagar is the main actor of the film who got rejected by 23 girls, yet he was optimistic about someone agreeing on him). Antara asked Swati to listen to her heart and breakup with Sagar if she is not happy and doesn't see any future with him.\nConvinced, as a result, Swati rejects Sagar's proposal and breaks up with him. This disheartens Sagar to a great extent. He was somehow consoled by his father.\nLater, when Sagar learns that it was because of Antara's advise that Swati rejected him, he decides to take revenge on her by following her to the Diu Trip, falsefully taking photos with her and making it a fake news in the newspaper inorder to make Antara fall in trouble with headlines.\nHe along with his friend (who was a photographer) manages to get information about Antara's Diu trip and boards the same bus which she boarded. Sagar continues his talks with Antara and manages to befriend her.\nHowever, Sagar fell in love with her as he started spending time with her in the trip. He asked his friend to avoid posting the fake news untill he tells him to do so.\nAntara also secretly felt for Sagar and she knew Sagar also felt for her.\nHowever, once when she was invited by Sagar for a birthday party at his home, she went to Sagar's room and checked all the pictures of her trip with Sagar in his laptop. This made her angry and hurted her a lot. She understood that Sagar didn't love her, but just used her to become famous.\nWhen she left the party, Sagar stopped her. She told everything. Sagar revealed about his anger on Antara when he came to know that her advise forced Swati to reject him. Antara realised that Sagar had planned a revenge and this hurted her more. She told Sagar not to talk with her henceforth.\nAaditya came to know about Sagar and Antara's Diu Trip, called Sagar to his office and warned him to stay away from Antara and avoid hurting her.\nLater, Aaditya proposed her for marriage, however Antara chose not to answer that.\nSagar then called her on her Radio Love Line and reminder her that without her, his life has become monotonous and he misses her alot.\nAntara ignored Sagar's calls and messages, and agreed to marry Aditya.\nSagar came to know about this and reached Antara's office, but her boss Krishna told Sagar to stay away from Antara and avoid hurting her more.\nBecause Antara was not responding Sagar's calls and messages, he sent her a letter asking whom she remembers the most when she gets up in the morning, when drinking coffee and when listening to songs online.\nSagar's friend later informs him that his boss is planning to post all the trip pictures in the newspaper next day to defame Antara.\nThis makes Sagar tensed, but he somehow manages to delete all the pictures from the boss' laptop with the help of his friend and snatches the pendrive having the backup, and throws it into the lake.\nAaditya happens to read the letter sent by Sagar at Antara's home when he came there to take out for coffee and he realised that she is not happy with the marriage.\nDespite asking Antara alot, she chooses to stay quiet and marry Aditya.\nDuring the marriage, Aaditya meets Antara and asks her to say the truth of whom she really thinks of in her mind. When Antara could not answer, Aditya told her that his aim was to see her happy, whether with him or with anyone else. Aaditya understood her mind and agreed to help her meet Sagar (who had already started giving up on his relationship with Antara).\nHowever, they were not able to locate him. Antara reached Radio office and asked Ahmedabad City to help her find Sagar. She manages to get help from a Tea Vendor where Sagar was sitting.\nAntara reaches that place and proposes Sagar by saying that she wants to forget her earlier anger and wants to start a new relationship with him, to which Sagar happily accepts.\nSagar thanked Aditya for such a huge sacrifise of his life.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Pratik Gandhi]] as Aaditya Shah\n* [[Aarohi Patel]] as RJ Antara\n* [[Malhar Thakar]] as Sagar Desai\n* [[Ghanashyam Nayak|Maulik Nayak]]\n*Diana Raval\n*Roopa Divatia\n*Nisarg Trivedi\n\n==Soundtrack==\nSoundtrack album was composed by famous [[Bollywood]] composer duo [[Sachin-Jigar]]. 'Vhalam Aavo Ne' was presented as a lead soundtrack for the album. There are mainly four soundtrack presented with other three being variations of the main tracks. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#ccc; text-align:center;\"\n! # !! Title !! Singer(s) !!  Length !!Lyrics !!Notes\n|-\n| 1 || Vhalam Aavo Ne || [[Jigardan Gadhavi]] || 05:19 || Niren Bhatt || Original version\n|-\n| 2 || Vhalam Aavo Ne \u2013 Sad(Female) || [[Aishwarya Majmudar]] || 02:24 || Niren Bhatt || Female sad version\n|-\n| 3 || Vhalam Aavo Ne \u2013 Sad(Male) || Jigardan Gadhavi || 01:44 || Niren Bhatt || Male sad version\n|-\n| 4 || Dhun Laagi || Siddharth Amit Bhavsar || 04:34 || Niren Bhatt || Original version\n|-\n| 5 || Dhun Laagi \u2013 Sad || Siddharth Amit Bhavsar || 01:47 || Niren Bhatt || Male sad version\n|-\n| 6 ||  Athdaya Karu Chhu || Punit Gandhi, Smita Nair Jain || 03:58 || Niren Bhatt || Only duet from album\n|-\n| 7 || I Love You Re Mari Savaar || [[Jonita Gandhi]] || 03:09 || Niren Bhatt || -\n|-\n|}\n\n==Reception==\nThe film achieved a critical and commercial success and ran for more than 100 days in the theatres.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chitralekha.com/news/entertainment/love-ni-bhavai/|title=\u0ab5\u0acd\u0ab9\u0abe\u0ab2\u0aae \u0a86\u0ab5\u0acb\u0aa8\u0ac7\u2026 \u0aae\u0abe\u0aa3\u0acb\u0aa8\u0ac7 \u0a86 \u0ab8\u0a95\u0acd\u0ab8\u0ac7\u0ab8-\u0a95\u0aa5\u0abe|date=28 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title}}\n*Love Ni Bhavai [https://www.netflix.com/in/title/80990811] on [[Netflix]]\n*\n\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Gujarati-language films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Ahmedabad]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Daman and Diu]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n\n\n{{India-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "BrainVE", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:typos", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_Ni_Bhavai"}
{"title_page": "Indian locomotive class WDM-2", "text_new": "{{under construction|altimage=|section=|nosection=|notready=|placedby=[[user:hdmanohar]]|comment=|nocat=|category=}}{{Infobox locomotive\n| name             = Indian locomotive class WDM-2 \n| powertype        = Diesel\n| image            = File:Changing tracks ... That&#039;s our life - Flickr - Dr. Santulan Mahanta.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = A GOC WDM-2 hauling an Express  \n| builder          = [[American Locomotive Company|Alco]], [[Diesel Locomotive Works|DLW]]\n| ordernumber      = \n| serialnumber     = \n| buildmodel       = [[ALCO DL560C|DL560C]]\n| builddate        = 1962-1998\n| totalproduction  = '''WDM-2/A/B:''' 1440<br />'''WDM-2G:''' 2\n| rebuilder        = \n| rebuilddate      = \n| numberrebuilt    = \n| Britishclass     = [[Co-Co locomotives|Co-Co]]\n| uicclass         = [[Co\u2032Co\u2032]]\n| gauge            = {{RailGauge|1676mm|lk=on}}\n| trucks           = \n| bogies           =ALCO Asymmetric cast frame trimount \n| wheeldiameter    = {{convert|1092|mm|ftin|0|abbr=on}}\n| trailingdiameter = \n| minimumcurve     = \n| wheelbase        = {{convert|12.834|m|ftin|abbr=on|frac=8}}\n| length           = {{convert|17.12|m|ftin|abbr=on|frac=8}}\n| width            = {{convert|2.864|m|ftin|abbr=on|frac=8}}\n| height           = {{convert|4.185|m|ftin|abbr=on|frac=8}}\n| axleload         = {{convert|18800|kg|abbr=on}}\n| weightondrivers  = \n| locoweight       = {{convert|112800|kg|abbr=on}}\n| fueltype         = [[Diesel fuel|Diesel]]\n| fuelcap          = {{convert|5000|L|abbr=on}}\n| lubecap          = \n| coolantcap       = \n| sandcap          = \n| consumption      = \n| primemover       = [[ALCO 251|ALCO 251-B]]\n| rpmrange         = 400 - 1000 rpm\n| enginetype       = [[V16 engine|V16]] [[Diesel engine|diesel]]\n| aspiration       = [[Turbo-supercharger|Turbo-supercharged]]\n| displacement     = \n| alternator       = \n| generator        = \n| tractionmotors   =[[General Electric|GE]]752, [[Bharat Heavy Electricals|BHEL]] 4906 BZ and 4907 AZ \n| cylindercount    = 16\n| cylindersize     = {{convert|228|x|266|mm|in|2|abbr=on}}<br /> [[Bore (engine)|bore]]\u00d7[[Stroke (engine)|stroke]]\n| transmission     =[[Diesel-electric transmission]] \n| multipleworking  =2 \n| maxspeed         = {{convert|120|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n| poweroutput      = Max:{{convert|2600|HP|abbr=on}}<br />Site rated:{{convert|2430|HP|abbr=on}}\n| tractiveeffort   ={{convert|30.4|t|0|abbr=on}} \n| factorofadhesion = 0.27\n| trainheating     = \n| locobrakes       = \n| locobrakeforce   = \n| trainbrakes      =[[Railway air brake|Air]], [[Vacuum brake|Vacuum]] and [[Vacuum brake#Dual brakes|Dual]] \n| safety           = \n| operator         =[[Indian Railways]] \n| operatorclass    = \n| powerclass       = \n| numinclass       = \n| fleetnumbers     =16000-16887, 17100-17999, 18040-18079, 18112-18514, 18523-18900, 18903-18999 \n| officialname     = \n| nicknames        =Jumbo, Prabal \n| axleloadclass    = \n| locale           =All over Indian Railways \n| deliverydate     = \n| firstrundate     = \n| lastrundate      = \n| retiredate       = \n| withdrawndate    = \n| preservedunits   =3 \n| restoredate      = \n| scrapdate        = \n| currentowner     = \n| disposition      = active\n}}\n\nThe Indian locomotive class '''WDM-2''' is a class of [[diesel-electric locomotive]] that was developed in the 1962 by [[American Locomotive Company]] (ALCO ) for [[Indian Railways]]. The model name stands for [[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|broad gauge (W)]], '''D'''iesel (D), '''M'''ixed traffic (M) engine, '''2'''nd generation (2)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco.html#class|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Locomotives - General Information - I|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. A total of 2700+ WDM-2 were built at ALCO and [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] (DLW), Varanasi between 1962 and 1998, which made them the most numerous class of mainline diesel locomotive till its successor the [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A|WDM-3A.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-specs.html|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Diesel and Electric Locomotive Specifications|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nThe WDM-2 is one of the most successful locomotives of Indian Railways serving both passenger and freight trains for over 58 years. Despite the introduction of more modern types of locomotives like [[Indian locomotive class WDG-4|WDG-4]] and electrification, a significant number are still in use, both on mainline and departmental duties. As of January 2020, 30 locomotives still exist as WDM-2, with further examples having been converted to [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A|WDM-3A]] or WDM-2S. 30 retain \"operational status\" on the mainline.\n\n== Origin ==\nThe history of WDM-2 begins in the early 1960s with the stated aim of the [[Indian Railways]] to remove [[steam locomotive]]s from Indian Rails. It therefore required a large build of [[Co-Co locomotives|Co-Co]] diesel locomotives with [[road switcher]] cabs to achieve this aim. This required locomotives producing at least 2,600&nbsp;hp (1,900&nbsp;kW) and began looking at various [[Diesel-electric train|diesel-electric]] designs.\n\nInitially, the Indian railways invited tenders to build locomotives to the new specification.The following responses were received:\n\n* ALCO submitted their model(RSD29 / DL560C) with 2600&nbsp;hp, 16-cylinder, 4-stroke turbo-supercharged engine with Co-Co bogies.\n* [[Electro-Motive Diesel|General Motors Electro-Motive Division]] (EMD) submitted their [[EMD SD24|SD24]], given model number GT16 for the India export version. They had Co-Co bogies with 16-cylinder 2-stroke turbo-supercharged engines.\n\nEach company submitted prototypes and Indian Railways designated these prototypes as the WDM-2 class and [[Indian locomotive class WDM-4|WDM-4]] class respectively. Technologically the General Motors WDM-4 was superior to ALCO's WDM-2, but Indian Railways required a transfer of technology agreement that would allow these locomotives to be ingeniously manufactured in India. Since General Motors did not agree to the transfer of technology agreement, the ALCO prototype was selected for production.\n\nHowever, even before the arrival of WDM-2 another type of diesel locomotive was imported from ALCo beginning in 1957. This locomotive was classified as [[Indian locomotive class WDM-1|WDM-1]].However WDM-1s were not selected for mass production because of having only one forward cab at one end which needed a lot of turntables. \n\n== Production History ==\n[[File:Indian diesel loco WDM2.jpg|thumb|295x295px|18040 the first WDM2 built preserved at national rail museum.|alt=]]\nThe first few prototype WDM-2 were imported with #18040 being the first WDM-2 of India. The need for a large number of locomotives quickly was deemed paramount. After [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] (DLW) completed construction of its factory in Varanasi, production of the locomotives began in India.The first 12 locos were built using kits imported from ALCO(order no. D3389) in the United States. \n\nThe first diesel loco assembled in DLW being #18233<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3732|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Mughalsarai (MGS) WDM-2 18233 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> and the first fully-built WDM-2 from DLW was 18299<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3798|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Bondamunda (BNDM) WDM-2 18299 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>. After that DLW started manufacturing the WDM-2 locomotives from their own components. Since then over 2,800 locomotives have been manufactured and the WDM-2 has become the most popular locomotive in India with the very last one being #16887.\n[[File:Kundan, the first WDM-2 locomotive assembled at DLW, Varanasi.jpg|thumb|289x289px|Kundan, the first WDM-2 locomotive assembled at DLW, Varanasi]]\nWhile ALCO went bankrupt, DLW varanasi successfully adapted the technology and produced may upgraded versions which were exported to many Broad Gauge countries. Later a number of modifications were made and a few sub classes were created. This includes WDM-2A, WDM-2B and WDM-3A (formerly WDM-2C). Now a few WDM-2 locos are being rebuilt by [[Diesel-Loco Modernisation Works|Diesel Loco Modernization Works]] (DLMW) Patiala, Punjab. These are fitted with Daulat Ram [[Dynamic braking|DBR]]'s.\n\n== Service History ==\nKatni(KTE) was the first shed to hold WDM2. The whole batch of WDM2 imports had all went to KTE. #18040 was first loco in the series, but 18042 was the first commissioned. Third DLS is listed as gooty(GY) in 1963 and first loco was WDM2 18207. Fourth DLS is listed as Itarsi(ET) in 1964 and first loco was WDM2 18043, so it got transfers from KTE initially. Fifth DLS is listed asErode([[Diesel loco shed, Erode|ED]]) in 1966. Sixth DLS is listed asRatlam(RTM) in 1967 and first loco was #18417.\n\nBy 1967 the first trains were being migrated to diesel and the initial high speed foray was the [[Mumbai Rajdhani Express|Mumbai Rajdhani]] with the WDM-2. The other trains dieselised were the premier mails and expresses where the WDM2 ( and  to a lesser and localized extent,the WDM4)  hauled an augmented load of 17 coaches and shaved off 4 to 5 hours over a 1500 km run particularly in systems where WP speeds were lower than other double-line systems like ER,CR and WR.\n\nSome of the trains were end to end WDM2 like the [[Himgiri Superfast Express|Himgiri]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world-railways.co.uk/photo/images/113.jpg|title=WDM-2 with himgiri|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[Tamil Nadu Express|Tamil Nadu]] but some were electric hauled for the part run. All averaged speeds well over 65 kmph. Some had the benefit of double line traction  but the Himgiri was running on large single line stretches  and the Tamil Nadu managed over 70 kmph.The WDM-2 locos have a maximum speed of {{convert|120|km/h|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"interactive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/docs/wdm2-interactive.html|title=Interactive Diagram of the WDM-2 Locomotive|author=Sheeju Chandran|date=|work=|publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club|accessdate=April 2, 2010}}</ref> restricted to {{convert|100|km/h|abbr=on}} when run long hood forward - the gear ratio is 65:18.\n\n=== Maintenance ===\nThe WDM-2 had a maintenance schedule of 3000km or 10-days which was recommended by ALCO. These have been extended by 20 days to 30 days by using better and more efficient lubrication oils and other component fluids and improving some bearings for the suspension.The original WDM-2 bearings were very failure prone and often required minor repairing.However the WDM-2 was very easy to operate and maintain because of its simple construction and mechanics and was very reliable.This maintenance is usually done at the nearest Diesel loco shed.\n\n== Sub-classes ==\n\n=== WDM-2A ===\nThe '''WDM-2A''' is a variant of the original WDM-2. These units have been retro-fitted with [[air brake (rail)|air brake]]s, in addition to the original [[vacuum brake]]s.So these locos have dual braking capacity.Despite this some WDM-2A are still marked as WDM-2 only\n\n=== WDM-2B ===\nThe '''WDM-2B''' is a more recent locomotive, built with air brakes as original equipment. They do not have Vacuum brakes. Only some have been classified as WDM-2B.\n\n=== Jumbos ===\n[[File:WDM-2 Diesel loco of PUNE.jpg|thumb|Jumbo variant of the WDM-2|287x287px]]\nThe WDM-2 locos from serial numbers around 17788 to 17890<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3461?authenticity_token=1f1Qxu9tgr7S3q+aySo3YvzVrC0l6leDud+8JTLwvRk=&loco_class_id=11&page=17|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Shakurbasti (SSB) WDM-2 17890 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>  to were fitted with full-width short hood with intention of giving them an extended visibility for the drivers. These are unofficially termed 'Jumbos' by crew and Rail-fans. WDM-2 #17722<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3293?authenticity_token=1f1Qxu9tgr7S3q+aySo3YvzVrC0l6leDud+8JTLwvRk=&loco_class_id=11&page=14|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Mughalsarai (MGS) WDM-2 17722 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> and 17748<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3319?authenticity_token=1f1Qxu9tgr7S3q+aySo3YvzVrC0l6leDud+8JTLwvRk=&loco_class_id=11&page=14|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Vishakapatnam (VSKP) WDM-2 17748 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> are rumored to be the prototypes of the jumbo class, but differs slightly<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://st2.indiarailinfo.com/kjfdsuiemjvcya0/0/3/2/7/1214327/0/img0781.jpg|title=17722 'JUMBO'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> from other Jumbos. But these locos proved to be not that useful as the loco pilots raised their concerns that they had to stand up to operate them. So a few were modified to have normal short hoods of WDM-2.Some earlier Jumbos were also converted to WDM-3A.\n\nThese locomotives are easy recognizable by short hood with big windows. After Over-ageing of these locomotives, the jumbos were mainly used on Shunting or Departmental works trains. As a consequence few of them are still in service\n\n=== WDM-2S ===\nThis classification are given to WDM-2 which are nearing the end of their service life. These locos can be easily recognized by '0' at the beginning of their road number. These WDM-2 locos are relegated to do Shunting or occasionally haul Departmental works trains.Some WDM-2 remain in classification for many years before they are scrapped.  \n\n== Variants ==\n\n=== WDM-3A ===\n{{Main|Indian locomotive class WDM-3A}}\nThe WDM-3A class are actually upgraded WDM-2 designed to produce more power ( 3100hp instead of 2600hp) and increased reliability (roller bearings instead of conventional ALCO bearings). Except for some 150 units, the rest are actually rebuilt WDM-2.  Rebuilt WDM3As can be identified by a \u201cR\u201d at the end of their Road Number.\n\n=== WDG-2/3A ===\n{{Main|Indian locomotive class WDG-2/3A}}It is the dedicated freight version of the [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2]] and shares the same engine and horsepower rating with [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A|WDM-3A]].The [[Bogie|Bogies]] of WDM-2 have been replaced by High adhesion Fabricated bogies for better traction and Stability. They are hugely successful with about 1163 units of this class have been produced.\n\n=== WDM-7 ===\n{{Main|Indian locomotive class WDM-7}}\n[[File:WDM7 BioDiesel.JPG|left|thumb|238x238px|A [[Indian locomotive class WDM-7|WDM-7]] can be recognized by lack of grilles on the short hood]]\nThey are lower powered('''2000 hp instead of 2600 hp)''' version of the WDM-2. These locos were built from 1987 to 1989. A few were at [[Diesel Loco Shed, Ernakulam|Ernakulam]] earlier but later all were transferred to [[Tondiarpet railway station|Tondiarpet]] seen shunting at Chennai Central or for light passenger haulage. Some are at the thermal power station, Chennai.\n\nThese Co-Co diesel-electrics were designed for branch-line duties (top speed 105 km/h). They have two 3-axle bogies and are similar to the WDM-2 in appearance. The power-pack is a 12-cylinder ALCO 251B unit. They were formerly housed at [[Diesel Loco Shed, Erode|Erode]] and [[Diesel Loco Shed, Golden Rock|Golden Rock]] also. They are reliable and rugged locomotives even though low powered. They can be easily recognized by the lack of grilles on the short hood. Two locos are running on a mixture of bio-diesel and diesel. All 15 are still in service.\n\n\n=== WDP-1 ===\n{{Main|Indian locomotive class WDP-1}}\nIt is a lower powered passenger ('''2300 hp)''' version of the [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2]]. The [[Bogie|Bogies]] of WDM-2 have been replaced by Bo-Bo fabricated bogies. They were not hugely successful. About 69 units have been produced with 60 locos still being in service. They are easily identified by baldie grille-less short hood.\n\n<br />\n\n== Some of the sheds holding WDM-2/A/B/G locomotives ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=60em|\n* [[Abu Road railway station|Abu Road]] - 3\n* [[Guwahati railway station|New Guwahati]] - 4\n* [[Jamalpur railway station|Jamalpur]] - 1\n* [[Jhansi Junction railway station|Jhansi]] - 1\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed Kurla]] - 1\n* [[New Katni Jn. railway station|New Katni Jn.]] - 1 \n* [[Malda Town railway station|Malda Town]] - 8\n* [[Mughalsarai Junction railway station|Mughalsarai]] - 2\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Golden Rock|Golden Rock]] - 3\n* [[Raipur Junction railway station|Raipur]] - 2\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed Tondiarpet]] - 4\n''' Total Locomotioves active in service as of 01-03-2020:''' 30<br />('''Note-'''Before updating the information here anybody should check out the railways current official data first in the  '''Source''' link then change the data.)\n}}\n<br />'''Source:''' http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,541,710,717\n\n== Former Sheds ==\n\n* [[Andal Junction railway station|Andal]] (UDL)\n* [[Bardhaman railway station|Bardhaman]] (BWN)\n* [[Bokaro Steel City railway station|Bokaro Steel City]] (BKSC)\n* [[Bondamunda railway station|Bondamunda]] (BNDM) \n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Ernakulam|Ernakulam]] (ERS)- The very last WDM-2 (18701) was removed from service on june, 2019 after being in the shed for 38 years.\n* [[Diesel loco shed, Erode|Erode]] (ED)\n* [[Gondal railway station|Gonda]] (GD)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Gooty|Gooty]] (GY)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Guntakal|Guntakal]] (GTL)\n* [[Howrah Junction railway station|Howrah]] (HWH)\n* [[Itarsi Junction railway station|Itarsi]] (ET)\n* [[Izzatnagar railway station|Izzatnagar Loco Shed]] (IZN)\n* [[Kalyan Junction railway station|Kalyan]] (KYN)\n* [[Kazipet railway station|Kazipet]] (KZJ)\n* [[Kharagpur Junction railway station|Kharagpur]] (KGP)\n* [[Krishnarajapuram railway station|Krishnarajapuram]] (KJM)\n* [[Lucknow Charbagh railway station|Lucknow]] (LKO)\n* [[Ludhiana Junction railway station|Ludhiana]] (LDH)\n* [[Moula Ali Railway Station|Moula Ali]] (MLY)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Pune|Pune]] (PUNE)\n* [[Patratu railway station|Loco Shed Patratu]] (PTRU)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Ratlam|Ratlam]] (RTM)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Samastipur|Samastipur]] (SPJ)\n* [[Tughlakabad railway station|Tughlakabad]] (TKD)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Vatva|Vatva]] (VTA)\n* [[Visakhapatnam railway station|Visakhapatnam]] (VSKP)\n\n== Liveries ==\n\n* GOC: ICF Rajdhani livery but red replaced by green. Logo was of the Rockfort.\n* TNP: Light and dark blue bottom. Flying bird on blue background was the logo. Few biodiesel ones were green.\n* ERS: A Kerala based logo with characteristic ICF rajdhani livery.\n* ED: Prancing deer of IR, dark blue with white.\n* KJM (SWR): blue and yellow and logo has SWR written in white on blue background.\n* Bondamunda had a red yellow maroon livery somewhat similar to VSKP \n* BKSC boasted of the green orange livery similar to bangladeshi national flag.\n\n== Loco Road numbers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-specs.html#WDM-2|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Diesel and Electric Locomotive Specifications|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> ==\nDuring the manufacture of WDM-2, DLW built these locos in non chronological matter.\n\n=== 18040-079/18112-18232 series locomotives ===\nThese locomotive were among the first WDM-2s to roam India. #18040 is the first ALCO of India and this series to be imported and subsequent ones were later supplied by ALCO. '''Locos numbers from 18080 to 18111 are actually WDM-4 class'''.These WDM-2 locos can be easily identified by their original ALCO dynamic brake vents with three partitions.These locos were mostly in mainline service till 2007 and were relegated to shunting/departmental duties thereafter. The last of these locos #18068 (from kurla) were condemned by March 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3599?authenticity_token=U9HEYXFBNAqEtWRMEtwNhQXa/0BcMQt2UINkU4HXAzs=&loco_class_id=11&page=19|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Kurla (CLA) WDM-2 18068 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>.All of these locomotive have been withdrawn from service and Scrapped.\n\n=== 18232-18514 series locomotives ===\nAfter 18232, DLW started manufacturing locos from kits supplied by ALCO. The first kit-built from DLW was 18233 name 'kundan' and subsequent ones were later assembled in DLW from kits supplied by ALCO after technology transfer took place.some of these (ex 18236) have retained their original ALCO dynamic brake vents with three partitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3735?authenticity_token=U9HEYXFBNAqEtWRMEtwNhQXa/0BcMQt2UINkU4HXAzs=&loco_class_id=11&page=22|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Erode (ED) WDM-2 18236 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. The first fully-built WDM-2 from DLW was 18299.These locos were mostly in mainline service till 2007 and were relegated to shunting/departmental duties thereafter like ALCO built ones. The last of these locos # 18473 were condemned by November 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3971?authenticity_token=U9HEYXFBNAqEtWRMEtwNhQXa/0BcMQt2UINkU4HXAzs=&loco_class_id=11&page=26|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Itarsi (ET) WDM-2 18473 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n'''After 18514, DLW started manufacturing locos with 17 series''' \n\n=== 17100-17999/17xxx series locomotives ===\nDLW stopped 18 series midway (18499) and started producing 17xxx series locomotives.'''Locos numbers from 17000 to 17099 are WDM-1 class.''' These were fully-built WDM-2 locos from DLW. The loco numbers 17796-17895 are the 'Jumbo' versions of WDM-2. Almost all of the jumbos WDM-2 belongs to this series.Most of these locos were manufactures in the 70's. The 17 series locomotives are no more used for Mainline services, these are now fit only for shunting and inferior activities with most of them being condemned/scrapped.\n\n'''18514-18522 are WDM3's built by German Manufacturers [[Henschel & Son|Henschel.]]'''\n\n=== 18523-18900/18903-18999 series locomotives ===\nThe locomotives numbering from 18530+ onward were manufactured from early 1980's. Almost all locos were rebuilt to WDM-3A standards but most reverted back to WDM-2 standards as they reach the end of their service life. A few are still in mainline service as WDM-3As. Most of them are fit only for shunting and inferior activities with half of them being condemned/scrapped. They still have about 1-2 years of service left in them.\n\n'''18901 and 18902 are WDM-6 which are no longer in service'''\n\n=== 16000-16887/16xxx series locomotives ===\n16xxx series are the youngest in the WDM-2 series. The oldest of their series #16001 was manufactured in mid 80's. They are originally WDM2's and all were rebuilt to WDM-3A standards except for locos lost to accident damage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/list?authenticity_token=U9HEYXFBNAqEtWRMEtwNhQXa/0BcMQt2UINkU4HXAzs=&loco_class_id=11&page=1|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster List|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. All 16 series locomotives are still running in mainline duties as WDM-3A class. Few (30) remained as pure WDM-2s are still in service.Scrapping/Condemning of 16xxx series has now begun.\n\n== Preserved Examples<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,1706|title=Ministry of Railways (Railway Board)|webs