r=on}}\n| tractiveeffort   ={{convert|30.4|t|0|abbr=on}} \n| factorofadhesion = 0.27\n| trainheating     = \n| locobrakes       = \n| locobrakeforce   = \n| trainbrakes      =[[Railway air brake|Air]], [[Vacuum brake|Vacuum]] and [[Vacuum brake#Dual brakes|Dual]] \n| safety           = \n| operator         =[[Indian Railways]] \n| operatorclass    = \n| powerclass       = \n| numinclass       = \n| fleetnumbers     =16000-16887, 17100-17999, 18040-18079, 18112-18514, 18523-18900, 18903-18999 \n| officialname     = \n| nicknames        =Jumbo, Prabal \n| axleloadclass    = \n| locale           =All over Indian Railways \n| deliverydate     = \n| firstrundate     = \n| lastrundate      = \n| retiredate       = \n| withdrawndate    = \n| preservedunits   =3 \n| restoredate      = \n| scrapdate        = \n| currentowner     = \n| disposition      = active\n}}\n\nThe Indian locomotive class '''WDM-2''' is a class of [[diesel-electric locomotive]] that was developed in the 1962 by [[American Locomotive Company]] (ALCO ) for [[Indian Railways]]. The model name stands for [[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|broad gauge (W)]], '''D'''iesel (D), '''M'''ixed traffic (M) engine, '''2'''nd generation (2)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco.html#class|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Locomotives - General Information - I|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>. A total of 2700+ WDM-2 were built at ALCO and [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] (DLW), Varanasi between 1962 and 1998, which made them the most numerous class of mainline diesel locomotive till its successor the [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A|WDM-3A.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-specs.html|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Diesel and Electric Locomotive Specifications|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\nThe WDM-2 is one of the most successful locomotives of Indian Railways serving both passenger and freight trains for over 58 years. Despite the introduction of more modern types of locomotives like [[Indian locomotive class WDG-4|WDG-4]] and electrification, a significant number are still in use, both on mainline and departmental duties. As of January 2020, 30 locomotives still exist as WDM-2, with further examples having been converted to [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A|WDM-3A]] or WDM-2S. 30 retain \"operational status\" on the mainline.\n\n== Origin ==\nThe history of WDM-2 begins in the early 1960s with the stated aim of the [[Indian Railways]] to remove [[steam locomotive]]s from Indian Rails. It therefore required a large build of [[Co-Co locomotives|Co-Co]] diesel locomotives with [[road switcher]] cabs to achieve this aim. This required locomotives producing at least 2,600&nbsp;hp (1,900&nbsp;kW) and began looking at various [[Diesel-electric train|diesel-electric]] designs.\n\nInitially, the Indian railways invited tenders to build locomotives to the new specification.The following responses were received:\n\n* ALCO submitted their model(RSD29 / DL560C) with 2600&nbsp;hp, 16-cylinder, 4-stroke turbo-supercharged engine with Co-Co bogies.\n* [[Electro-Motive Diesel|General Motors Electro-Motive Division]] (EMD) submitted their [[EMD SD24|SD24]], given model number GT16 for the India export version. They had Co-Co bogies with 16-cylinder 2-stroke turbo-supercharged engines.\n\nEach company submitted prototypes and Indian Railways designated these prototypes as the WDM-2 class and [[Indian locomotive class WDM-4|WDM-4]] class respectively. Technologically the General Motors WDM-4 was superior to ALCO's WDM-2, but Indian Railways required a transfer of technology agreement that would allow these locomotives to be ingeniously manufactured in India. Since General Motors did not agree to the transfer of technology agreement, the ALCO prototype was selected for production.\n\nHowever, even before the arrival of WDM-2 another type of diesel locomotive was imported from ALCo beginning in 1957. This locomotive was classified as [[Indian locomotive class WDM-1|WDM-1]].However WDM-1s were not selected for mass production because of having only one forward cab at one end which needed a lot of turntables. \n\n== Production History ==\n[[File:Indian diesel loco WDM2.jpg|thumb|325x325px|18040 the first WDM2 built preserved at national rail museum.|alt=]]\nThe first few prototype WDM-2 were imported with #18040 being the first WDM-2 of India. The need for a large number of locomotives quickly was deemed paramount. After [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] (DLW) completed construction of its factory in Varanasi, production of the locomotives began in India.The first 12 locos were built using kits imported from ALCO(order no. D3389) in the United States. \n\nThe first diesel loco assembled in DLW being #18233<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3732|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Mughalsarai (MGS) WDM-2 18233 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> and the first fully-built WDM-2 from DLW was 18299<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3798|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Bondamunda (BNDM) WDM-2 18299 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>. After that DLW started manufacturing the WDM-2 locomotives from their own components. Since then over 2,800 locomotives have been manufactured and the WDM-2 has become the most popular locomotive in India with the very last one being #16887.\n[[File:Kundan, the first WDM-2 locomotive assembled at DLW, Varanasi.jpg|thumb|324x324px|Kundan, the first WDM-2 locomotive assembled at DLW, Varanasi]]\nWhile ALCO went bankrupt, DLW varanasi successfully adapted the technology and produced may upgraded versions which were exported to many Broad Gauge countries. Later a number of modifications were made and a few sub classes were created. This includes WDM-2A, WDM-2B and WDM-3A (formerly WDM-2C). Now a few WDM-2 locos are being rebuilt by [[Diesel-Loco Modernisation Works|Diesel Loco Modernization Works]] (DLMW) Patiala, Punjab. These are fitted with Daulat Ram [[Dynamic braking|DBR]]'s.\n\n== Service History ==\nKatni(KTE) was the first shed to hold WDM2. The whole batch of WDM2 imports had all went to KTE. #18040 was first loco in the series, but 18042 was the first commissioned. Third DLS is listed as gooty(GY) in 1963 and first loco was WDM2 18207. Fourth DLS is listed as Itarsi(ET) in 1964 and first loco was WDM2 18043, so it got transfers from KTE initially. Fifth DLS is listed asErode([[Diesel loco shed, Erode|ED]]) in 1966. Sixth DLS is listed asRatlam(RTM) in 1967 and first loco was #18417.\n\nBy 1967 the first trains were being migrated to diesel and the initial high speed foray was the [[Mumbai Rajdhani Express|Mumbai Rajdhani]] with the WDM-2. The other trains dieselised were the premier mails and expresses where the WDM2 ( and  to a lesser and localized extent,the WDM4)  hauled an augmented load of 17 coaches and shaved off 4 to 5 hours over a 1500 km run particularly in systems where WP speeds were lower than other double-line systems like ER,CR and WR.\n\nSome of the trains were end to end WDM2 like the [[Himgiri Superfast Express|Himgiri]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.world-railways.co.uk/photo/images/113.jpg|title=WDM-2 with himgiri|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> and [[Tamil Nadu Express|Tamil Nadu]] but some were electric hauled for the part run. All averaged speeds well over 65 kmph. Some had the benefit of double line traction  but the Himgiri was running on large single line stretches  and the Tamil Nadu managed over 70 kmph.The WDM-2 locos have a maximum speed of {{convert|120|km/h|abbr=on}},<ref name=\"interactive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.irfca.org/docs/wdm2-interactive.html|title=Interactive Diagram of the WDM-2 Locomotive|author=Sheeju Chandran|date=|work=|publisher=Indian Railways Fan Club|accessdate=April 2, 2010}}</ref> restricted to {{convert|100|km/h|abbr=on}} when run long hood forward - the gear ratio is 65:18.\n\n=== Maintenance ===\nThe WDM-2 had a maintenance schedule of 3000km or 10-days which was recommended by ALCO. These have been extended by 20 days to 30 days by using better and more efficient lubrication oils and other component fluids and improving some bearings for the suspension.The original WDM-2 bearings were very failure prone and often required minor repairing.However the WDM-2 was very easy to operate and maintain because of its simple construction and mechanics and was very reliable.This maintenance is usually done at the nearest Diesel loco shed.\n\n== Sub-classes ==\n\n=== WDM-2A ===\nThe '''WDM-2A''' is a variant of the original WDM-2. These units have been retro-fitted with [[air brake (rail)|air brake]]s, in addition to the original [[vacuum brake]]s.So these locos have dual braking capacity.Despite this some WDM-2A are still marked as WDM-2 only\n\n=== WDM-2B ===\nThe '''WDM-2B''' is a more recent locomotive, built with air brakes as original equipment. They do not have Vacuum brakes. Only some have been classified as WDM-2B.\n\n=== Jumbos ===\n[[File:WDM-2 Diesel loco of PUNE.jpg|thumb|Jumbo variant of the WDM-2|287x287px]]\nThe WDM-2 locos from serial numbers around 17788 to 17890<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3461?authenticity_token=1f1Qxu9tgr7S3q+aySo3YvzVrC0l6leDud+8JTLwvRk=&loco_class_id=11&page=17|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Shakurbasti (SSB) WDM-2 17890 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>  to were fitted with full-width short hood with intention of giving them an extended visibility for the drivers. These are unofficially termed 'Jumbos' by crew and Rail-fans. WDM-2 #17722<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3293?authenticity_token=1f1Qxu9tgr7S3q+aySo3YvzVrC0l6leDud+8JTLwvRk=&loco_class_id=11&page=14|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Mughalsarai (MGS) WDM-2 17722 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> and 17748<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3319?authenticity_token=1f1Qxu9tgr7S3q+aySo3YvzVrC0l6leDud+8JTLwvRk=&loco_class_id=11&page=14|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Vishakapatnam (VSKP) WDM-2 17748 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> are rumored to be the prototypes of the jumbo class, but differs slightly<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://st2.indiarailinfo.com/kjfdsuiemjvcya0/0/3/2/7/1214327/0/img0781.jpg|title=17722 'JUMBO'|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> from other Jumbos. But these locos proved to be not that useful as the loco pilots raised their concerns that they had to stand up to operate them. So a few were modified to have normal short hoods of WDM-2.Some earlier Jumbos were also converted to WDM-3A.\n\nThese locomotives are easy recognizable by short hood with big windows. After Over-ageing of these locomotives, the jumbos were mainly used on Shunting or Departmental works trains. As a consequence few of them are still in service\n\n=== WDM-2S ===\nThis classification are given to WDM-2 which are nearing the end of their service life. These locos can be easily recognized by '0' at the beginning of their road number. These WDM-2 locos are relegated to do Shunting or occasionally haul Departmental works trains.Some WDM-2 remain in classification for many years before they are scrapped.  \n\n== Variants ==\n\n=== WDM-3A ===\n{{Main|Indian locomotive class WDM-3A}}\nThe WDM-3A class are actually upgraded WDM-2 designed to produce more power ( 3100hp instead of 2600hp) and increased reliability (roller bearings instead of conventional ALCO bearings). Except for some 150 units, the rest are actually rebuilt WDM-2.  Rebuilt WDM3As can be identified by a \u201cR\u201d at the end of their Road Number.\n\n=== WDG-2/3A ===\n{{Main|Indian locomotive class WDG-2/3A}}\n\n=== WDP-3A ===\n{{Main|Indian locomotive class WDP-3A}}\n\n=== WDM-7 ===\n{{Main|Indian locomotive class WDM-7}}\n<br />\n\n== Some of the sheds holding WDM-2/A/B/G locomotives ==\n{{columns-list|colwidth=60em|\n* [[Abu Road railway station|Abu Road]] - 3\n* [[Guwahati railway station|New Guwahati]] - 4\n* [[Jamalpur railway station|Jamalpur]] - 1\n* [[Jhansi Junction railway station|Jhansi]] - 1\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed Kurla]] - 1\n* [[New Katni Jn. railway station|New Katni Jn.]] - 1 \n* [[Malda Town railway station|Malda Town]] - 8\n* [[Mughalsarai Junction railway station|Mughalsarai]] - 2\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Golden Rock|Golden Rock]] - 3\n* [[Raipur Junction railway station|Raipur]] - 2\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed Tondiarpet]] - 4\n''' Total Locomotioves active in service as of 01-03-2020:''' 30<br />('''Note-'''Before updating the information here anybody should check out the railways current official data first in the  '''Source''' link then change the data.)\n}}\n<br />'''Source:''' http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,541,710,717\n\n== Former Sheds ==\n\n* [[Andal Junction railway station|Andal]] (UDL)\n* [[Bardhaman railway station|Bardhaman]] (BWN)\n* [[Bokaro Steel City railway station|Bokaro Steel City]] (BKSC)\n* [[Bondamunda railway station|Bondamunda]] (BNDM) \n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Ernakulam|Ernakulam]] (ERS)- The very last WDM-2 (18701) was removed from service on june, 2019 after being in the shed for 38 years.\n* [[Diesel loco shed, Erode|Erode]] (ED)\n* [[Gondal railway station|Gonda]] (GD)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Gooty|Gooty]] (GY)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Guntakal|Guntakal]] (GTL)\n* [[Howrah Junction railway station|Howrah]] (HWH)\n* [[Itarsi Junction railway station|Itarsi]] (ET)\n* [[Izzatnagar railway station|Izzatnagar Loco Shed]] (IZN)\n* [[Kalyan Junction railway station|Kalyan]] (KYN)\n* [[Kazipet railway station|Kazipet]] (KZJ)\n* [[Kharagpur Junction railway station|Kharagpur]] (KGP)\n* [[Krishnarajapuram railway station|Krishnarajapuram]] (KJM)\n* [[Lucknow Charbagh railway station|Lucknow]] (LKO)\n* [[Ludhiana Junction railway station|Ludhiana]] (LDH)\n* [[Moula Ali Railway Station|Moula Ali]] (MLY)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Pune|Pune]] (PUNE)\n* [[Patratu railway station|Loco Shed Patratu]] (PTRU)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Ratlam|Ratlam]] (RTM)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Samastipur|Samastipur]] (SPJ)\n* [[Tughlakabad railway station|Tughlakabad]] (TKD)\n* [[Diesel Loco Shed, Vatva|Vatva]] (VTA)\n* [[Visakhapatnam railway station|Visakhapatnam]] (VSKP)\n\n== Liveries ==\n\n* GOC: ICF Rajdhani livery but red replaced by green. Logo was of the Rockfort.\n* TNP: Light and dark blue bottom. Flying bird on blue background was the logo. Few biodiesel ones were green.\n* ERS: A Kerala based logo with characteristic ICF rajdhani livery.\n* ED: Prancing deer of IR, dark blue with white.\n* KJM (SWR): blue and yellow and logo has SWR written in white on blue background.\n* Bondamunda had a red yellow maroon livery somewhat similar to VSKP \n* BKSC boasted of the green orange livery similar to bangladeshi national flag.\n\n== Loco Road numbers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-specs.html#WDM-2|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Diesel and Electric Locomotive Specifications|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> ==\nDuring the manufacture of WDM-2, DLW built these locos in non chronological matter.\n\n=== 18040-079/18112-18232 series locomotives ===\nThese locomotive were among the first WDM-2s to roam India. #18040 is the first ALCO of India and this series to be imported and subsequent ones were later supplied by ALCO. '''Locos numbers from 18080 to 18111 are actually WDM-4 class'''.These WDM-2 locos can be easily identified by their original ALCO dynamic brake vents with three partitions.These locos were mostly in mainline service till 2007 and were relegated to shunting/departmental duties thereafter. The last of these locos #18068 (from kurla) were condemned by March 2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3599?authenticity_token=U9HEYXFBNAqEtWRMEtwNhQXa/0BcMQt2UINkU4HXAzs=&loco_class_id=11&page=19|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Kurla (CLA) WDM-2 18068 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>.All of these locomotive have been withdrawn from service and Scrapped.\n\n=== 18232-18514 series locomotives ===\nAfter 18232, DLW started manufacturing locos from kits supplied by ALCO. The first kit-built from DLW was 18233 name 'kundan' and subsequent ones were later assembled in DLW from kits supplied by ALCO after technology transfer took place.some of these (ex 18236) have retained their original ALCO dynamic brake vents with three partitions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3735?authenticity_token=U9HEYXFBNAqEtWRMEtwNhQXa/0BcMQt2UINkU4HXAzs=&loco_class_id=11&page=22|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Erode (ED) WDM-2 18236 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. The first fully-built WDM-2 from DLW was 18299.These locos were mostly in mainline service till 2007 and were relegated to shunting/departmental duties thereafter like ALCO built ones. The last of these locos # 18473 were condemned by November 2013<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3971?authenticity_token=U9HEYXFBNAqEtWRMEtwNhQXa/0BcMQt2UINkU4HXAzs=&loco_class_id=11&page=26|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Itarsi (ET) WDM-2 18473 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n'''After 18514, DLW started manufacturing locos with 17 series''' \n\n=== 17100-17999/17xxx series locomotives ===\nDLW stopped 18 series midway (18499) and started producing 17xxx series locomotives.'''Locos numbers from 17000 to 17099 are WDM-1 class.''' These were fully-built WDM-2 locos from DLW. The loco numbers 17796-17895 are the 'Jumbo' versions of WDM-2. Almost all of the jumbos WDM-2 belongs to this series.Most of these locos were manufactures in the 70's. The 17 series locomotives are no more used for Mainline services, these are now fit only for shunting and inferior activities with most of them being condemned/scrapped.\n\n'''18514-18522 are WDM3's built by German Manufacturers [[Henschel & Son|Henschel.]]'''\n\n=== 18523-18900/18903-18999 series locomotives ===\nThe locomotives numbering from 18530+ onward were manufactured from early 1980's. Almost all locos were rebuilt to WDM-3A standards but most reverted back to WDM-2 standards as they reach the end of their service life. A few are still in mainline service as WDM-3As. Most of them are fit only for shunting and inferior activities with half of them being condemned/scrapped. They still have about 1-2 years of service left in them.\n\n'''18901 and 18902 are WDM-6 which are no longer in service'''\n\n=== 16000-16887/16xxx series locomotives ===\n16xxx series are the youngest in the WDM-2 series. The oldest of their series #16001 was manufactured in mid 80's. They are originally WDM2's and all were rebuilt to WDM-3A standards except for locos lost to accident damage<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/list?authenticity_token=U9HEYXFBNAqEtWRMEtwNhQXa/0BcMQt2UINkU4HXAzs=&loco_class_id=11&page=1|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster List|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. All 16 series locomotives are still running in mainline duties as WDM-3A class. Few (30) remained as pure WDM-2s are still in service.Scrapping/Condemning of 16xxx series has now begun.\n\n== Preserved Examples<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,1706|title=Ministry of Railways (Railway Board)|website=www.indianrailways.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1L7PMD3GYsSQibjrOjIk9dpekeDi7Gp9u|title=preserve loco list|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Class\n!Manufacturer\n!Loco Number\n!Previous shed\n!Name\n!LIvery\n!Location\n!ref\n|-\n|WDM-2B\n|DLW\n|17263\n|Malda Town (MLDT)\n|\n|MLDT blue/cream/blue with red lining\n|To be plinthed at Kishanganj (KNE) station of Katihar Division, NFR [20/12/2013]\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/2834?list_type=preserved|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Malda Town (MLDT) WDM-2 17263 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|WDM-2\n|DLW\n|17445\n|Kazipet (KZJ)\n|\n|\n|Earmarked for preservation: I.R. Heritage Website [November 2018]\n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4560?list_type=preserved&page=2</ref>\n|-\n|WDM-3A/2A\n|DLW\n|17754\n|Ludhiana (LDH)\n|\n|LDH grey/red/grey with white lining\n|Earmarked for preservation: I.R. Heritage Website [November 2018]\n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3325?list_type=preserved</ref>\n|-\n|WDM-2\n|ALCO\n|18040\n|Katni(KTE)\n|\n|Maroon with yellow lining & blue Stripes\n|Preserved at National Railway Museum, Delhi\n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3571?list_type=preserved</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/gallery/Trips/north/Vicky-misc/IMG_2130.jpg.html|title=First Wdm-2 pic|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|-\n|WDM-2\n|ALCo\n|18119\n|Itarsi (ET)\n|\n|Light blue with white band\n|Plinthed at Zonal Railway Training Institute, Bhusaval\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/uv?hl=en&pb=!1s0x3bd9a5eb86459be9%3A0x2c5c4e4e37329d93!3m1!7e115!4shttps%3A%2F%2Flh5.googleusercontent.com%2Fp%2FAF1QipPvNmCeyuzqQFdn3QxVc1Aym_iOkkgk-k1NHFMs%3Dw213-h160-k-no!5sZonal%20Railway%20Training%20Institute%2C%20Bhusawal%2018119%20-%20Google%20Search&imagekey=!1e10!2sAF1QipNQ7r1LQKdYds0ggU8VM364zs8niVE5VSejAI_4&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjWpMPRh-3oAhVYzzgGHZk-A5sQoiowG3oECBgQBg|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3618?list_type=preserved</ref>\n|-\n|WDM-2A\n|ALCo\n|18160\n|Ernakulam (ERS)\n|\n|Red\n|This loco is preserved in GOC workshop.\n|<ref>https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3659?list_type=preserved&page=2</ref>\n|-\n|WDM-2\n|DLW\n|18233\n|Mughalsarai (MGS)\n|Kundan\n|Red/white/grey\n|Permanent Exhibit at DLW,Varanasi\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/3732?list_type=preserved&page=2|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Mughalsarai (MGS) WDM-2 18233 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|WDM-2B\n|DLW\n|18575\n|Malda Town (MLDT)\n|\n|MLDT blue/cream/blue with red lining\n|Earmarked for preservation: I.R. Heritage Website [November 2018]\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4065?list_type=preserved&page=2|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Malda Town (MLDT) WDM-2 18575 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|-\n|WDM-2/3A\n|DLW\n|18599\n|Krishnarajapuram (KJM)\n|\n|KJM blue/turquoise/blue with blue lining\n|Plinthed at SWR Headquarters Office - Rail Soudha, Hubballi, glass panels on one side\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/apps/locos/show/4089?list_type=preserved&page=2|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways Locomotive Roster Krishnarajapuram (KJM) WDM-3A 18599 Show|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== Technical specifications<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2d.html|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Locomotives -- Specific classes : AC Electric|website=www.irfca.org}}</ref> ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Manufacturers\n|Alco, DLW\n|-\n|Engine\n|Alco 251-B, [[V16 engine|16 cylinder engine]], {{convert|2600|hp|abbr=on|lk=on}} ({{convert|2430|hp|abbr=on|disp=or}} site rating) with Alco 710/720/?? turbo supercharged engine. 1,000 rpm max, 400 rpm idle; {{convert|228|x|266|mm|in|2|abbr=on}} bore x stroke; compression ratio 12.5:1. Direct fuel injection, centrifugal pump cooling system ({{convert|2,457|L/min|abbr=on|disp=or}} at 1,000 rpm), fan driven by eddy current clutch ({{convert|86|hp|abbr=on|disp=or}} at 1,000 rpm)\n|-\n|Governor\n|[[General Electric|GE]] 17MG8 / Woodwards 8574-650 / Medha MEG 601\n|-\n|Transmission\n|Electric, with [[BHEL]] TG 10931 AZ generator (1,000 rpm, 770 V, 4,520 A)\n|-\n|[[Traction motor]]s\n|GE752 (original Alco models) ({{convert|405|hp|abbr=on|disp=or}}), BHEL 4906 BZ (AZ?) ({{convert|435|hp|abbr=on|disp=or}}) and (newer) 4907 AZ (with roller bearings)\n|-\n|[[Axle load]]\n|{{convert|18.8|t|abbr=on}}  \n|-\n|total weight\n|{{convert|112.8|t|abbr=on}}\n|-\n|[[Bogie]]s\n|Alco design cast frame trimount ([[Co-Co engine|Co-Co]]) bogies \n|-\n|Starting TE\n|{{convert|30.4|t|abbr=on}}, at adhesion 27%\n|-\n|Length over [[buffer beam]]s\n|{{convert|15,862|mm|ftin|abbr=on|frac=8}}\n|-\n|Distance between [[bogie]]s\n|{{convert|10,516|mm|ftin|abbr=on|frac=8}}\n|}\n\n== Export versions ==\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\n[[File:SLR M8 Loco.jpg|thumb|300px|WDM-2 - Class M8 In Sri Lanka]]\n{{Main|Sri Lanka Railways M8}}\n\nEight WDM-2 locomotives were purchased by [[Sri Lanka Railways]], the state run railroad operator in [[Sri Lanka]] in 1996. They were the longest and most powerful locomotives owned by Sri Lanka Railways at that time. They were allocated the '''M8''' class.<ref>{{Cite web\n  |url=https://slrailinfo.wordpress.com/locomotives/class-m/class-m8/\n  |title=Class M8|date=September 18, 2012\n}}</ref> However some modifications to the appearance were done by SLR.<ref>{{Cite web\n  |url=https://locolanka.blogspot.com/2011/02/m8.html\n  |title=\u0df4\u0d85\u0d9f\u0dd4\u0dbb\u0dd4 \u0db1\u0ddc\u0d9a\u0dcf \u0dc0\u0dad\u0dd4\u0dbb \u0db1\u0ddc\u0db6\u0dd3 \u0d9a\u0ddc\u0dc5\u0db9 \u0daf\u0dd4\u0dc0\u0db1 \u0dba\u0d9a\u0da9 \u0dba\u0d9a\u0dcf\u0df4: \u0df4M8 \u0daf\u0dd4\u0db8\u0dca\u0dbb\u0dd2\u0dba \u0d91\u0db1\u0dca\u0da2\u0dd2\u0db8 - \u0d85\u0db4\u0dda \u0d85\u0dc3\u0dbd\u0dca\u0dc0\u0dd0\u0dc3\u0dd2 \u0dbb\u0da7 \u0dc0\u0db1 \u0d89\u0db1\u0dca\u0daf\u0dd2\u0dba\u0dcf\u0dc0\u0dda \u0db1\u0dd2\u0dc2\u0dca\u0db4\u0dcf\u0daf\u0db1\u0dba\u0d9a\u0dca\u0df4|date=February 6, 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n==== Fleet<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.srilankanlocos.com/cgi-sys/suspendedpage.cgi|title=Account Suspended|website=www.srilankanlocos.com|access-date=June 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190320235704/http://www.srilankanlocos.com/cgi-sys/suspendedpage.cgi|archive-date=March 20, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country !! Railroad !! Class !! Quantity !! Road Numbers !! Notes\n|-\n| [[Sri Lanka]] || [[Sri Lanka Railways]] || [[Sri Lanka Railways M8|M8]] || 8 || 841 - 848 || All locomotives are operational.\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[History of rail transport in India]]\n* [[Locomotives of India]]\n* [[Rail transport in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Indian locomotive class WDM2}}\n\n===Notes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Hughes-IndianLocos4}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{Broad gauge locomotives of India |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Diesel-electric locomotives of India]]\n[[Category:Co-Co locomotives]]\n[[Category:ALCO locomotives]]\n[[Category:Railway locomotives introduced in 1962]]\n[[Category:5 ft 6 in gauge locomotives]]\n", "name_user": "Hdmanohar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added info in variant section aboutWDM-7. user is the sole contributor of the text at the other page so attribution is not necessary.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_locomotive_class_WDM-2"}
{"title_page": "O-Cresolphthalein", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''o''-Cresolphthalein}}\n{{Chembox\n| Name           = ''o''-Cresolphthalein\n| ImageFile      = O-Kresolphthalein.svg\n| ImageSize      = \n| ImageAlt       = \n| ImageName      = \n| IUPACName      = 3,3-Bis(4-hydroxy-3-methylphenyl)-1(3''H'')-isobenzofuranone\n| SystematicName = \n| OtherNames     = \n| Section1       = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| 3DMet = \n| Abbreviations = \n| Beilstein = 5-18-04-00193\n| CASNo = 596-27-0\n| CASNo_Ref = \n| CASNoOther = \n| ChEBI = \n| ChEMBL = 1443546\n| ChemSpiderID = 62217\n| DrugBank = \n| EC_number = 209-881-8\n| EINECS = \n| Gmelin = \n| InChI=1S/C22H18O4/c1-13-11-15(7-9-19(13)23)22(16-8-10-20(24)14(2)12-16)18-6-4-3-5-17(18)21(25)26-22/h3-12,23-24H,1-2H3\n| InChIKey = CPBJMKMKNCRKQB-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| KEGG = \n| MeSHName = \n| PubChem = 68995\n| RTECS = \n| SMILES = CC1=C(C=CC(=C1)C2(C3=CC=CC=C3C(=O)O2)C4=CC(=C(C=C4)O)C)O\n| UNNumber = \n| UNII = XOU2D9049G\n}}\n| Section2       = {{Chembox Properties\n| AtmosphericOHRateConstant = \n| Appearance = White powder\n| BoilingPt = 222.6 \u00b0C (432.68 \u00b0F; 495.75 K)\n| BoilingPt_notes = \n| Density = 82.7 g/mL\n| C=22 | H=18 | O=4\n| HenryConstant = \n| LogP = 1.975\n| MeltingPtC = 223\n| MeltingPt_notes = \n| pKa = 9.61\n| pKb = \n| Solubility = Insoluble\n| SolubleOther = Soluble in [[ethanol]]\n| Solvent = \n| VaporPressure = }}\n| Section3       = {{Chembox Structure\n| Coordination = \n| CrystalStruct = \n| MolShape = }}\n| Section4       = {{Chembox Thermochemistry\n| DeltaHc = \n| DeltaHf = \n| Entropy = \n| HeatCapacity = }}\n| Section5       = \n| Section6       = \n| Section7       = {{Chembox Hazards\n| AutoignitionPt = \n| EUClass = \n| ExploLimits = \n| ExternalSDS = \n| FlashPt = \n| LD50 = \n| MainHazards = \n| NFPA-H = \n| NFPA-F = \n| NFPA-R = \n| NFPA-S = \n| PEL = \n| GHSPictograms = {{GHS07}}{{GHS08}}\n| GHSSignalWord = Warning\n| HPhrases = {{H-phrases|302|312|315|319|332|335|351}}\n| PPhrases = {{P-phrases|201|202|261|264|270|271|280|281|301+312|302+352|304+312|304+340|305+351+338|308+313|312|321|322|330|332+313|337+313|362|363|403+233|405|501}}\n}}\n| Section8       = {{Chembox Related\n| OtherFunction_label = \n| OtherAnions = \n| OtherCations = \n| OtherCompounds = [[Phenolphthalein]]<br>[[Thymolphthalein]]\n| OtherFunction = }}\n}}\n\n'''''o''-Cresolphthalein''' is a [[phthalein dye]] used as a [[pH indicator]] in [[titration]]s. It is insoluble in water but soluble in [[ethanol]]. Its solution is colourless below pH 8.2, and purple above 9.8. Its molecular formula is C<sub>22</sub>H<sub>18</sub>O<sub>4</sub>. It is used medically to determine calcium levels in the human body, or to synthesize polyamides or polyimides.\n\n== Production ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:A facile synthesis of pthalein indicator dyes REACTION by Sabnis, Ram w. 2009.jpg|left|thumb|295x295px|<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sabnis|first=Ram W.|date=2009-11-18|title=A facile synthesis of phthalein indicator dyes|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0040403909017171|journal=Tetrahedron Letters|language=en|volume=50|issue=46|pages=6261\u20136263|doi=10.1016/j.tetlet.2009.09.007|issn=0040-4039}}</ref>]] -->\no-Cresophthalein is not produced industrially, rather, it is commercially available.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Liu|first=Zhihong|last2=Liu|first2=Junfeng|last3=Chen|first3=Tianlu|date=2005|title=Facile synthesis, characterization, and potential applications of two kinds of polymeric pH indicators: Phenolphthalein formaldehyde and o-cresolphthalein formaldehyde|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/pola.20576|journal=Journal of Polymer Science Part A: Polymer Chemistry|language=en|volume=43|issue=5|pages=1019\u20131027|doi=10.1002/pola.20576|issn=1099-0518}}</ref> To be produced, the method generally used to synthesize phthalein dyes is effective. This method is used to synthesize [[phenolphthalein]] and [[thymolphthalein]]. To begin, a 2M equivalent of a [[phenol]] or a substituted phenol should be combined with a 1M equivalent of a [[phthalic anhydride]]. However, if the phenol is substituted, the carbon para to the hydroxyl carbon must not be substituted. Anhydrous [[methanesulfonic acid]] should be present as a condensing agent and a solvent that will dehydrate. The combined compounds should be mixed at 90\u00b0C for 5 hours. The temperature should not reach 100\u00b0C at any point. The mixture should then be cooled to room temperature and, once precipitated, added to ice water. The product should then be filtered, washed, and dried. The crude product should then be [[Recrystallization (chemistry)|recrystallized]] with an appropriate solvent with charcoal treatment-furnished pure thalein dyes. The color after recrystallization should be between a light brown and a soft yellow. <ref name=\":0\" /> The described reaction as described is above.   \n\n== Uses ==\nThe compound has uses ranging from medicine to laboratory syntheses of chemically similar compounds. o-Cresophthalein has been used to derive [[Polyamide|polyamides]] and [[Polyimide|polyimides]], colorimetrically estimate [[calcium]] in serum, and predict amount of time to wait before blood collection after a patient receives [[gadodiamide]].  \n\n=== Deriving Polyamides and Polyimides ===\nAromatic polyamides and polyamides are practical compounds due to their temperature resistance, electrical or insulating characteristics, and their mechanical strength. Some of the polyamides and polyimides that can be synthesized by o-Cresophthalein are [[polycarbonate]], [[Acrylate polymer|polyacrylate]], and [[Epoxy resin|epoxy-resin]]. \n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Screen Shot 2020-04-11 at 9.53.31 PM.png|thumb|alt=|left]] --><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe diether-diamine 3,3-bis[4-(4-amino-phenoxy)-3-methylphenyl]phthalide, or BNMP, is synthesized by 12 g o-cresophthalein, 11.5 g ''p''-chloronitrobenzene, 5.1 g anhydrous potassium carbonate, and 55 mL of DMF. The compounds should be refluxed together at 160\u00b0C for eight hours. Once it is done and has cooled, it should be mixed with 0.3 L methanol. A precipitate should form and be vacuum filtered to obtain a solid. It should then be washed with water and dried, yielding a yellow product. It should then be recrystallized from glacial acetic acid to yield yellow needles. The product is BNMP. The reaction can go further by combining 15.5 g of BNMP with 0.18 g 10% Pd/C and 50 mL ethanol. They should be stirred at 80 \u00b0C. 7 mL of hydrazine monohydrate should be added drop by drop for one hour. The solution should then be mixed for eight hours. It should then be filtered to separated from the Pd/C and concentrated. The concentrated solution should be added to water, and a precipitate should be formed. It should then be vacuum filtered to isolate the solid, yelding 3,3-Bis[4-(4-aminophenoxy)-3-methylphenyl]pthalide, or BAMP, as a white solid. It should then be purified by water and ethanol.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Chin-Ping|last2=Tang|first2=Sheng-Yuan|date=1999|title=Syntheses and properties of organosoluble polyamides and polyimides based on the diamine 3,3-bis[4-(4-aminophenoxy)-3-methylphenyl]phthalide derived from o-cresolphthalein|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/%28SICI%291099-0518%2819990215%2937%3A4%3C455%3A%3AAID-POLA9%3E3.0.CO%3B2-3|journal=Journal of Polymer Science Part A: Polymer Chemistry|language=en|volume=37|issue=4|pages=455\u2013464|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1099-0518(19990215)37:43.0.CO;2-3|issn=1099-0518}}</ref> The described reaction is displayed on the left.\n\n=== Colorimetric Estimation of Calcium in Serum ===\nCalcium in a blood sample should be estimated when required medically. Calcium should be precipitated out of 0.1 mL of the blood sample serum as calcium oxalate. After that, the decomposition of the calcium oxalate should occur by heat. Then, the sample should be estimated colorimetrically by o-cresolphthalein complexone. The required liquid complexone is made by dissolving 10 mg o-cresolphthalein complexone in 50 mL alkaline borate, and then 50 mL of 0.05 N HCl are added to make the solution's pH 8.5. This method for calcium determination is efficient and effective, requiring a minimal amount of blood serum sample and a reasonable amount of time. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stern|first=J.|last2=Lewis|first2=W.H.P.|date=1957|title=The colorimetric estimation of calcium in serum with o-cresolphthalein complexone|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/0009898157900633|journal=Clinica Chimica Acta|volume=2|issue=6|pages=576\u2013580|doi=10.1016/0009-8981(57)90063-3|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Determination of Impact of Gadodiamide on Calcium Measurements ===\nGadolinium is given to patients for magnetic resonance imaging, or an MRI.It is used as a contrast agent for the exam to improve clarity of the images formed. However, it can react in the human body and have detrimental effects. Therefore, the agent should be removed. One of these gadolinium based agents is gadodiamide. Calcium in the body should be determined accurately to ensure that the Gadodiamide does not have adverse effects on the patient. There are two o-cresolphthalein methods to determine amount of calcium. The o-cresolpthalein methods are effective because it is a calcium binding dye. The gadodinium ion with a charge of +3 can be removed from gadodiamide using o-cresolphthalein. For these methods, glomerular filtration rate, or GFR, and time since gadodiamide was given should be recorded. Ultimately, these two factors and the impact of gadodiamide on calcium levels calculated by the o-cresolphthalein method helps to reveal an amount of time that patients must wait after receiving gadodiamide to have blood drawn again, or avoid pseudohypocalcemia.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kang|first=Hyunseok Peter|last2=Scott|first2=Mitchell G|last3=Joe|first3=Bonnie N|last4=Narra|first4=Vamsi|last5=Heiken|first5=Jay|last6=Parvin|first6=Curtis A|date=2004-04-01|title=Model for Predicting the Impact of Gadolinium on Plasma Calcium Measured by the o-Cresolphthalein Method|url=https://academic.oup.com/clinchem/article/50/4/741/5639850|journal=Clinical Chemistry|language=en|volume=50|issue=4|pages=741\u2013746|doi=10.1373/clinchem.2003.028886|issn=0009-9147}}</ref>\n\n== Safety ==\n\n=== NFPA Diamond ===\n[[File:NFPA-704-NFPA-Diamonds-Sign-000.png|left|thumb]]\n<br />{{pH_indicator_template|indicator_name=Cresolphthalein |low_pH=8.2 |high_pH=9.8|low_pH_color=white|high_pH_color=purple|high_pH_text=white}}\nTo the left is the NFPA diamond as determined by the Safety Data Sheet, or SDS, by Fisher Scientific. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sabnis|first=Ram W.|date=2009-11-18|title=A facile synthesis of phthalein indicator dyes|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0040403909017171|journal=Tetrahedron Letters|language=en|volume=50|issue=46|pages=6261\u20136263|doi=10.1016/j.tetlet.2009.09.007|issn=0040-4039}}</ref> There is minimal risk in handling the chemical. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20150924095330/http://www.sciencelab.com/msds.php?msdsId=9923574\n*http://www.chemicaldictionary.org/dic/O/o-Cresolphthalein_1298.html\n*http://www.chemspider.com/Chemical-Structure.62217.html\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cresolphthalein2}}\n[[Category:PH indicators]]\n[[Category:Triarylmethane dyes]]\n\n\n{{organic-chemistry-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''o''-Cresolphthalein}}\n{{Chembox\n| Name           = ''o''-Cresolphthalein\n| ImageFile      = O-Kresolphthalein.svg\n| ImageSize      = \n| ImageAlt       = \n| ImageName      = \n| IUPACName      = 3,3-Bis(4-hydroxy-3-methylphenyl)-1(3''H'')-isobenzofuranone\n| SystematicName = \n| OtherNames     = \n| Section1       = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| 3DMet = \n| Abbreviations = \n| Beilstein = 5-18-04-00193\n| CASNo = 596-27-0\n| CASNo_Ref = \n| CASNoOther = \n| ChEBI = \n| ChEMBL = 1443546\n| ChemSpiderID = 62217\n| DrugBank = \n| EC_number = 209-881-8\n| EINECS = \n| Gmelin = \n| InChI=1S/C22H18O4/c1-13-11-15(7-9-19(13)23)22(16-8-10-20(24)14(2)12-16)18-6-4-3-5-17(18)21(25)26-22/h3-12,23-24H,1-2H3\n| InChIKey = CPBJMKMKNCRKQB-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| KEGG = \n| MeSHName = \n| PubChem = 68995\n| RTECS = \n| SMILES = CC1=C(C=CC(=C1)C2(C3=CC=CC=C3C(=O)O2)C4=CC(=C(C=C4)O)C)O\n| UNNumber = \n| UNII = XOU2D9049G\n}}\n| Section2       = {{Chembox Properties\n| AtmosphericOHRateConstant = \n| Appearance = White powder\n| BoilingPt = 222.6 \u00b0C (432.68 \u00b0F; 495.75 K)\n| BoilingPt_notes = \n| Density = 82.7 g/mL\n| C=22 | H=18 | O=4\n| HenryConstant = \n| LogP = 1.975\n| MeltingPtC = 223\n| MeltingPt_notes = \n| pKa = 9.61\n| pKb = \n| Solubility = Insoluble\n| SolubleOther = Soluble in [[ethanol]]\n| Solvent = \n| VaporPressure = }}\n| Section3       = {{Chembox Structure\n| Coordination = \n| CrystalStruct = \n| MolShape = }}\n| Section4       = {{Chembox Thermochemistry\n| DeltaHc = \n| DeltaHf = \n| Entropy = \n| HeatCapacity = }}\n| Section5       = \n| Section6       = \n| Section7       = {{Chembox Hazards\n| AutoignitionPt = \n| EUClass = \n| ExploLimits = \n| ExternalSDS = \n| FlashPt = \n| LD50 = \n| MainHazards = \n| NFPA-H = \n| NFPA-F = \n| NFPA-R = \n| NFPA-S = \n| PEL = \n| GHSPictograms = {{GHS07}}{{GHS08}}\n| GHSSignalWord = Warning\n| HPhrases = {{H-phrases|302|312|315|319|332|335|351}}\n| PPhrases = {{P-phrases|201|202|261|264|270|271|280|281|301+312|302+352|304+312|304+340|305+351+338|308+313|312|321|322|330|332+313|337+313|362|363|403+233|405|501}}\n}}\n| Section8       = {{Chembox Related\n| OtherFunction_label = \n| OtherAnions = \n| OtherCations = \n| OtherCompounds = [[Phenolphthalein]]<br>[[Thymolphthalein]]\n| OtherFunction = }}\n}}\n\n'''''o''-Cresolphthalein''' is a [[phthalein dye]] used as a [[pH indicator]] in [[titration]]s. It is insoluble in water but soluble in [[ethanol]]. Its solution is colourless below pH 8.2, and purple above 9.8. Its molecular formula is C<sub>22</sub>H<sub>18</sub>O<sub>4</sub>. It is used medically to determine calcium levels in the human body, or to synthesize polyamides or polyimides.\n\n== Production ==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:A facile synthesis of pthalein indicator dyes REACTION by Sabnis, Ram w. 2009.jpg|left|thumb|295x295px|<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sabnis|first=Ram W.|date=2009-11-18|title=A facile synthesis of phthalein indicator dyes|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0040403909017171|journal=Tetrahedron Letters|language=en|volume=50|issue=46|pages=6261\u20136263|doi=10.1016/j.tetlet.2009.09.007|issn=0040-4039}}</ref>]] -->\no-Cresophthalein is not produced industrially, rather, it is commercially available.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Liu|first=Zhihong|last2=Liu|first2=Junfeng|last3=Chen|first3=Tianlu|date=2005|title=Facile synthesis, characterization, and potential applications of two kinds of polymeric pH indicators: Phenolphthalein formaldehyde and o-cresolphthalein formaldehyde|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/pola.20576|journal=Journal of Polymer Science Part A: Polymer Chemistry|language=en|volume=43|issue=5|pages=1019\u20131027|doi=10.1002/pola.20576|issn=1099-0518}}</ref> To be produced, the method generally used to synthesize phthalein dyes is effective. This method is used to synthesize [[phenolphthalein]] and [[thymolphthalein]]. To begin, a 2M equivalent of a [[phenol]] or a substituted phenol should be combined with a 1M equivalent of a [[phthalic anhydride]]. However, if the phenol is substituted, the carbon para to the hydroxyl carbon must not be substituted. Anhydrous [[methanesulfonic acid]] should be present as a condensing agent and a solvent that will dehydrate. The combined compounds should be mixed at 90\u00b0C for 5 hours. The temperature should not reach 100\u00b0C at any point. The mixture should then be cooled to room temperature and, once precipitated, added to ice water. The product should then be filtered, washed, and dried. The crude product should then be [[Recrystallize|recrystallized]] with an appropriate solvent with charcoal treatment-furnished pure thalein dyes. The color after recrystallization should be between a light brown and a soft yellow. <ref name=\":0\" /> The described reaction as described is above.   \n\n== Uses ==\nThe compound has uses ranging from medicine to laboratory syntheses of chemically similar compounds. o-Cresophthalein has been used to derive [[Polyamide|polyamides]] and [[Polyimide|polyimides]], colorimetrically estimate [[calcium]] in serum, and predict amount of time to wait before blood collection after a patient receives [[gadodiamide]].  \n\n=== Deriving Polyamides and Polyimides ===\nAromatic polyamides and polyamides are practical compounds due to their temperature resistance, electrical or insulating characteristics, and their mechanical strength. Some of the polyamides and polyimides that can be synthesized by o-Cresophthalein are [[polycarbonate]], [[Acrylate polymer|polyacrylate]], and [[Epoxy resin|epoxy-resin]]. \n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Screen Shot 2020-04-11 at 9.53.31 PM.png|thumb|alt=|left]] --><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe diether-diamine 3,3-bis[4-(4-amino-phenoxy)-3-methylphenyl]phthalide, or BNMP, is synthesized by 12 g o-cresophthalein, 11.5 g ''p''-chloronitrobenzene, 5.1 g anhydrous potassium carbonate, and 55 mL of DMF. The compounds should be refluxed together at 160\u00b0C for eight hours. Once it is done and has cooled, it should be mixed with 0.3 L methanol. A precipitate should form and be vacuum filtered to obtain a solid. It should then be washed with water and dried, yielding a yellow product. It should then be recrystallized from glacial acetic acid to yield yellow needles. The product is BNMP. The reaction can go further by combining 15.5 g of BNMP with 0.18 g 10% Pd/C and 50 mL ethanol. They should be stirred at 80 \u00b0C. 7 mL of hydrazine monohydrate should be added drop by drop for one hour. The solution should then be mixed for eight hours. It should then be filtered to separated from the Pd/C and concentrated. The concentrated solution should be added to water, and a precipitate should be formed. It should then be vacuum filtered to isolate the solid, yelding 3,3-Bis[4-(4-aminophenoxy)-3-methylphenyl]pthalide, or BAMP, as a white solid. It should then be purified by water and ethanol.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Yang|first=Chin-Ping|last2=Tang|first2=Sheng-Yuan|date=1999|title=Syntheses and properties of organosoluble polyamides and polyimides based on the diamine 3,3-bis[4-(4-aminophenoxy)-3-methylphenyl]phthalide derived from o-cresolphthalein|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/%28SICI%291099-0518%2819990215%2937%3A4%3C455%3A%3AAID-POLA9%3E3.0.CO%3B2-3|journal=Journal of Polymer Science Part A: Polymer Chemistry|language=en|volume=37|issue=4|pages=455\u2013464|doi=10.1002/(SICI)1099-0518(19990215)37:43.0.CO;2-3|issn=1099-0518}}</ref> The described reaction is displayed on the left.\n\n=== Colorimetric Estimation of Calcium in Serum ===\nCalcium in a blood sample should be estimated when required medically. Calcium should be precipitated out of 0.1 mL of the blood sample serum as calcium oxalate. After that, the decomposition of the calcium oxalate should occur by heat. Then, the sample should be estimated colorimetrically by o-cresolphthalein complexone. The required liquid complexone is made by dissolving 10 mg o-cresolphthalein complexone in 50 mL alkaline borate, and then 50 mL of 0.05 N HCl are added to make the solution's pH 8.5. This method for calcium determination is efficient and effective, requiring a minimal amount of blood serum sample and a reasonable amount of time. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Stern|first=J.|last2=Lewis|first2=W.H.P.|date=1957|title=The colorimetric estimation of calcium in serum with o-cresolphthalein complexone|url=https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/0009898157900633|journal=Clinica Chimica Acta|volume=2|issue=6|pages=576\u2013580|doi=10.1016/0009-8981(57)90063-3|via=}}</ref>\n\n=== Determination of Impact of Gadodiamide on Calcium Measurements ===\nGadolinium is given to patients for magnetic resonance imaging, or an MRI.It is used as a contrast agent for the exam to improve clarity of the images formed. However, it can react in the human body and have detrimental effects. Therefore, the agent should be removed. One of these gadolinium based agents is gadodiamide. Calcium in the body should be determined accurately to ensure that the Gadodiamide does not have adverse effects on the patient. There are two o-cresolphthalein methods to determine amount of calcium. The o-cresolpthalein methods are effective because it is a calcium binding dye. The gadodinium ion with a charge of +3 can be removed from gadodiamide using o-cresolphthalein. For these methods, glomerular filtration rate, or GFR, and time since gadodiamide was given should be recorded. Ultimately, these two factors and the impact of gadodiamide on calcium levels calculated by the o-cresolphthalein method helps to reveal an amount of time that patients must wait after receiving gadodiamide to have blood drawn again, or avoid pseudohypocalcemia.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kang|first=Hyunseok Peter|last2=Scott|first2=Mitchell G|last3=Joe|first3=Bonnie N|last4=Narra|first4=Vamsi|last5=Heiken|first5=Jay|last6=Parvin|first6=Curtis A|date=2004-04-01|title=Model for Predicting the Impact of Gadolinium on Plasma Calcium Measured by the o-Cresolphthalein Method|url=https://academic.oup.com/clinchem/article/50/4/741/5639850|journal=Clinical Chemistry|language=en|volume=50|issue=4|pages=741\u2013746|doi=10.1373/clinchem.2003.028886|issn=0009-9147}}</ref>\n\n== Safety ==\n\n=== NFPA Diamond ===\n[[File:NFPA-704-NFPA-Diamonds-Sign-000.png|left|thumb]]\n<br />{{pH_indicator_template|indicator_name=Cresolphthalein |low_pH=8.2 |high_pH=9.8|low_pH_color=white|high_pH_color=purple|high_pH_text=white}}\nTo the left is the NFPA diamond as determined by the Safety Data Sheet, or SDS, by Fisher Scientific. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sabnis|first=Ram W.|date=2009-11-18|title=A facile synthesis of phthalein indicator dyes|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0040403909017171|journal=Tetrahedron Letters|language=en|volume=50|issue=46|pages=6261\u20136263|doi=10.1016/j.tetlet.2009.09.007|issn=0040-4039}}</ref> There is minimal risk in handling the chemical. \n\n\n\n\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20150924095330/http://www.sciencelab.com/msds.php?msdsId=9923574\n*http://www.chemicaldictionary.org/dic/O/o-Cresolphthalein_1298.html\n*http://www.chemspider.com/Chemical-Structure.62217.html\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cresolphthalein2}}\n[[Category:PH indicators]]\n[[Category:Triarylmethane dyes]]\n\n\n{{organic-chemistry-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toRecrystallization(link changed toRecrystallization (chemistry)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O-Cresolphthalein"}
{"title_page": "Somerville College Boat Club", "text_new": "{{Infobox rowing club\n| name         = Somerville College Boat Club\n| emblem       = {{scarf|{{cells|3|red}}{{cell|black}}{{cells|2|red}}{{cell|black}}{{cells|3|red}}{{cell|black}}{{cells|2|red}}{{cell|black}}{{cells|3|red}}}}\n| image        = [[File:University College Oxford Boat Club Boathouse.JPG|290px]]\n| blade_image  = [[File:Somerville College Boat Club Rowing Blade.svg|200px]]\n| caption      = Boathouse (owned by University College) and rowing blade colours\n| motto        =  \n| location     = [[University College Boathouse]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51.742171|N|1.24961|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title|name=Somerville College Boat Club}}\n| home_water   = The Isis \n| founded      = {{Start date|1921}}\n| former_names = \n| head_label   = Senior Member\n| head         = \n| president    = Toby Sanderson (Men's), Rachel Donnachie & Lucy Bannatyne (Women's)\n| captain      = {{ubl\n | Men: Pak Hei Hao\n | Women: Kieran Storer & Charlotte Yates\n }}\n| captain_of_coxes = Elinor Lamrick\n| members      = \n| champs_label = [[Eights Week|Head of the River]]\n| champs       = {{ubl\n | Men: \n | Women: 1980, 1981, 1986, 1987, 1990\u201393\n }}\n| colours      = {{color box|Red}} {{color box|Black}} \n| university   = [[University of Oxford]]\n| affiliations = [[Girton College Boat Club]] ([[List of Oxbridge sister colleges|Sister college]])\n| website      = {{URL|http://somervilleboatclub.weebly.com/}}\n}}\n'''Somerville College Boat Club''' ('''SCBC''') is the [[rowing club]] of [[Somerville College, Oxford]]. The club was formed in 1921 as one of the first women's clubs on the [[The Isis| Isis]], however was unable to compete in bumps until 1969. The women's team has won the title ''Head of the River'' eight times in [[Summer Eights]] and five times in [[Torpids]], more than any other women's rowing team from the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\"ox\">{{cite web|url=http://eodg.atm.ox.ac.uk/user/dudhia/rowing/bumps/estats/index.html|website=eodg.atm.ox.ac.uk|title=Eights Statistics|accessdate=2018-08-15}}</ref>\n\nDue to fears that it might harm their reproductive abilities, women's rowing clubs were banned until 1921. A member of the club was first permitted to take part in Summer Eights in 1927, following the rejection of an earlier request in 1922.{{sfn|Adams|1996|pp=209-10}}\n\nNow there are 6 women's divisions in [[Summer Eights]] and racing in the top divisions is as competitive as the men's. However, when women were first given their own division, only 12 colleges competed - Somerville, as an all women's college, was one of them. Within four years the W1 were Head of the River.<ref name=\"weebly\">{{cite web|url=http://somervilleboatclub.weebly.com/history.html|title=History - SOMERVILLE COLLEGE BOAT CLUB|website=somervilleboatclub.weebly.com|accessdate=2018-08-15}}</ref>\n\nSomerville College Boat Club shares the [[University College Boathouse]] with [[University College, Oxford|University College]], [[St Peter's College, Oxford|St Peter's College]] and [[Wolfson College, Oxford|Wolfson College]]. The building is owned by University College and won a [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] prize and has enjoyed a very favourable reception in the architectural world.<ref>[http://www.oxfordmail.net/news/headlines/display.var.2325153.0.new_college_boathouse_scoops_design_award.php \"New college boathouse scoops design award\"], ''[[Oxford Mail ]]''.</ref><ref>[http://www.architecture.com/Awards/RIBAAwards/Winners2008/South/UniversityCollegeBoathouse/UniversityCollegeBoathouse.aspx University College Boathouse, Oxford], [http://www.architecture.com/ artitecture.com].</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni of SCBC==\nSomerville College Boat Club has produced four [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] rowers:<ref>[http://www.ox.ac.uk/about/oxford-people/Oxford-at-the-Olympics Oxford at the Olympics]</ref>\n*[[Fiona Freckleton]], bronze medalist in the Women's Pairs at the [[1991 World Rowing Championships]] in Vienna  - Great Britain's first medal in a major World Championship women's rowing event<ref>{{cite news |title=Tributes for coach Proudley |url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/11013495.Tributes_for_coach_Proudley/ |accessdate=14 September 2018 |work=[[Southern Daily Echo]] |date=15 February 2014}}</ref> - also competed at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] and [[1993 World Rowing Championships]].\n*[[Patricia Reid (rower)|Patricia Reid]] also competed at the 1992 Summer Olympics, having achieved silver and bronze at the [[1986 Commonwealth Games]].\n*[[Luka Grubor]], gold medalist at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]], [[2002 World Rowing Championships]] and 1993 [[World Rowing U23 Championships|Nations Cup]], silver medalist at the [[1999 World Rowing Championships]].\n*[[Jennifer Goldsack]], competed at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]]; gold medalist at the [[2011 Pan American Games]] and silver medalist at the [[2007 World Rowing Championships]].\n\nOther notable members of the SCBC were [[Lucy Sutherland]] and [[Dominica Legge]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{harvid|Adams|1996}}|last1=Adams|first1=Pauline|title=Somerville for Women: An Oxford College, 1879-1993|date=1996|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199201822|edition=}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://somervilleboatclub.weebly.com/|title=SOMERVILLE COLLEGE BOAT CLUB - Home|website=somervilleboatclub.weebly.com|accessdate=2018-08-15}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.britishrowing.org/club/somerville-college-boat-club/|title=Somerville College Boat Club|website=British Rowing|accessdate=2018-08-15}}\n\n{{Oxford University Rowing Clubs}}\n\n[[Category:Somerville College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Rowing clubs of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1921]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rowing club\n| name         = Somerville College Boat Club\n| emblem       = {{scarf|{{cells|3|red}}{{cell|black}}{{cells|2|red}}{{cell|black}}{{cells|3|red}}{{cell|black}}{{cells|2|red}}{{cell|black}}{{cells|3|red}}}}\n| image        = [[File:University College Oxford Boat Club Boathouse.JPG|290px]]\n| blade_image  = [[File:Somerville College Boat Club Rowing Blade.svg|200px]]\n| caption      = Boathouse (owned by University College) and rowing blade colours\n| motto        =  \n| location     = [[University College Boathouse]]\n| coordinates  = {{coord|51.742171|N|1.24961|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title|name=Somerville College Boat Club}}\n| home_water   = The Isis \n| founded      = {{Start date|1921}}\n| former_names = \n| head_label   = Senior Member\n| head         = \n| president    = Toby Sanderson (Men's), Rachel Donnachie & Lucy Bannatyne (Women's)\n| captain      = {{ubl\n | Men: Pak Hei Hao\n | Women: Kieran Storer & Charlotte Yates\n }}\n| captain_of_coxes = Elinor Lamrick\n| members      = \n| champs_label = [[Eights Week|Head of the River]]\n| champs       = {{ubl\n | Men: \n | Women: 1980, 1981, 1986, 1987, 1990\u201393\n }}\n| colours      = {{color box|Red}} {{color box|Black}} \n| university   = [[University of Oxford]]\n| affiliations = [[Girton College Boat Club]] ([[List of Oxbridge sister colleges|Sister college]])\n| website      = {{URL|http://somervilleboatclub.weebly.com/}}\n}}\n'''Somerville College Boat Club''' ('''SCBC''') is the [[rowing club]] of [[Somerville College, Oxford]]. The club was formed in 1921 as one of the first women's clubs on the [[The Isis| Isis]], however was unable to compete in bumps until 1969. The women's team has won the title ''Head of the River'' eight times in [[Summer Eights]] and five times in [[Torpids]], more than any other women's rowing team from the [[University of Oxford]].<ref name=\"ox\">{{cite web|url=http://eodg.atm.ox.ac.uk/user/dudhia/rowing/bumps/estats/index.html|website=eodg.atm.ox.ac.uk|title=Eights Statistics|accessdate=2018-08-15}}</ref>\n\nDue to fears that it might harm the theirs reproductive abilities, women's rowing clubs were banned until 1921. A member of the club was first permitted to take part in Summer Eights in 1927, following the rejection of an earlier request in 1922.{{sfn|Adams|1996|pp=209-10}}\n\nNow there are 6 women's divisions in [[Summer Eights]] and racing in the top divisions is as competitive as the men's. However, when women were first given their own division, only 12 colleges competed - Somerville, as an all women's college, was one of them. Within four years the W1 were Head of the River.<ref name=\"weebly\">{{cite web|url=http://somervilleboatclub.weebly.com/history.html|title=History - SOMERVILLE COLLEGE BOAT CLUB|website=somervilleboatclub.weebly.com|accessdate=2018-08-15}}</ref>\n\nSomerville College Boat Club shares the [[University College Boathouse]] with [[University College, Oxford|University College]], [[St Peter's College, Oxford|St Peter's College]] and [[Wolfson College, Oxford|Wolfson College]]. The building is owned by University College and won a [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] prize and has enjoyed a very favourable reception in the architectural world.<ref>[http://www.oxfordmail.net/news/headlines/display.var.2325153.0.new_college_boathouse_scoops_design_award.php \"New college boathouse scoops design award\"], ''[[Oxford Mail ]]''.</ref><ref>[http://www.architecture.com/Awards/RIBAAwards/Winners2008/South/UniversityCollegeBoathouse/UniversityCollegeBoathouse.aspx University College Boathouse, Oxford], [http://www.architecture.com/ artitecture.com].</ref>\n\n==Notable alumni of SCBC==\nSomerville College Boat Club has produced four [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] rowers:<ref>[http://www.ox.ac.uk/about/oxford-people/Oxford-at-the-Olympics Oxford at the Olympics]</ref>\n*[[Fiona Freckleton]], bronze medalist in the Women's Pairs at the [[1991 World Rowing Championships]] in Vienna  - Great Britain's first medal in a major World Championship women's rowing event<ref>{{cite news |title=Tributes for coach Proudley |url=https://www.dailyecho.co.uk/sport/11013495.Tributes_for_coach_Proudley/ |accessdate=14 September 2018 |work=[[Southern Daily Echo]] |date=15 February 2014}}</ref> - also competed at the [[1992 Summer Olympics]] and [[1993 World Rowing Championships]].\n*[[Patricia Reid (rower)|Patricia Reid]] also competed at the 1992 Summer Olympics, having achieved silver and bronze at the [[1986 Commonwealth Games]].\n*[[Luka Grubor]], gold medalist at the [[2000 Summer Olympics]], [[2002 World Rowing Championships]] and 1993 [[World Rowing U23 Championships|Nations Cup]], silver medalist at the [[1999 World Rowing Championships]].\n*[[Jennifer Goldsack]], competed at the [[2008 Summer Olympics]]; gold medalist at the [[2011 Pan American Games]] and silver medalist at the [[2007 World Rowing Championships]].\n\nOther notable members of the SCBC were [[Lucy Sutherland]] and [[Dominica Legge]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{harvid|Adams|1996}}|last1=Adams|first1=Pauline|title=Somerville for Women: An Oxford College, 1879-1993|date=1996|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford|isbn=9780199201822|edition=}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{cite web|url=http://somervilleboatclub.weebly.com/|title=SOMERVILLE COLLEGE BOAT CLUB - Home|website=somervilleboatclub.weebly.com|accessdate=2018-08-15}}\n*{{cite web|url=https://www.britishrowing.org/club/somerville-college-boat-club/|title=Somerville College Boat Club|website=British Rowing|accessdate=2018-08-15}}\n\n{{Oxford University Rowing Clubs}}\n\n[[Category:Somerville College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Rowing clubs of the University of Oxford]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs established in 1921]]\n[[Category:1921 establishments in England]]\n", "name_user": "Mtroper82", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Somerville_College_Boat_Club"}
